{"title_page": "Joseph Tapine", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Joe Tapine\n|fullname       = Joseph Tapine\n|image          = Joe Tapine.jpg\n|imagesize      = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1994|5|4}}\n|birth_place    = [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]\n|height         = {{convert|188|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|107|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|SR|LK}}\n|club1          = [[Newcastle Knights]]\n|year1start     = 2014\n|year1end       = 15\n|appearances1   = 20\n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 4\n|club2          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year2start     = 2016\n|year2end       = present\n|appearances2   = 80\n|tries2         = 14\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 56\n|teamA          = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearAstart     = 2016\n|yearAend       = present\n|appearancesA   = 9\n|triesA         = 2\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 8\n|teamB          = [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]]\t\n|yearBstart     = 2019\t\n|yearBend       =\n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/jospeh-tapine/summary.html|title=Joseph Tapine - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref><ref>[https://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Joseph-Tapine/ loverugbyleague]</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Tapine''' pronounced ({{IPAc-en|t|\u00e6|p|i\u02d0|n|\u025b}}) (born 4 May 1994), also known by the [[nickname]] of '''\"Joe\"''',<ref name=\"nrl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/knights-rookies-star-against-goannas/tabid/10874/newsid/76194/default.aspx|title=Knights rookies star against Goannas - NRL.com|publisher=nrl.com|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref> is a New Zealand professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|sr}} and {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. He has played for [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] and [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]] at international level. \n\nTapine previously played for the [[Newcastle Knights]] in the [[National Rugby League]].\n\n==Background==\nTapine was born in [[Wellington]], New Zealand and is of M\u0101ori and Cook Island descent. \n\nTapine played his junior rugby league for the [[Harbour City Eagles]]. He then joined the [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington Orcas]] in the [[New Zealand Rugby League]] [[National Competition]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early Career===\nIn 2013, Tapine joined the [[Newcastle Knights]] on a 1-year contract before re-signing for a further 3 years during the year.<ref name=\"newcastleknights2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/content/knights/club/members-only/knights_insider_wayne_bennett2.html|title=KNIGHTS INSIDER - Wayne Bennett - Knights|publisher=newcastleknights.com.au|accessdate=2014-07-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221312/http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/content/knights/club/members-only/knights_insider_wayne_bennett2.html|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref> He played for the Knights' [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team in 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://nycdatabase.org/players/t/|title=T|publisher=Nyc Database|date=|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> \nOn 13 October 2013, Tapine played for the [[Junior Kiwis]] against the [[Junior Kangaroos]], starting at second-row in the 38-26 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/nine-warriors-in-junior-kiwis-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/75024/default.aspx|title=Nine Warriors in Junior Kiwis squad|publisher=NRL.com|date=2013-10-08|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn Round 9 of the [[2014 NRL season]], Tapine made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the [[Newcastle Knights]] against the [[Penrith Panthers]], playing off the interchange bench in the 32-10 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/nrl-2014/round-9/newcastle-vs-penrith/summary.html|title=NRL 2014 - Round 9|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\"newcastleknights\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/news/2014/05/11/late_mail_knights_v_panthers.html|title=LATE MAIL: Knights v Panthers - Knights|publisher=newcastleknights.com.au|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref> Tapine finished off his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 7 matches for the Knights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTUtMTY0NC00LS0tLS0tMjA4MTctLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=2015-11-22|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> On 2 September 2014, Tapine was named on the [[Rugby league positions#Interchange|interchange bench]] in the 2014 NYC Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/holden-team-year-announced/|title=Holden Cup Team Of The Year Announced|publisher=Rugbyleagueweek.com.au|date=2014-09-02|accessdate=2015-06-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626101814/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/holden-team-year-announced/|archivedate=2015-06-26}}</ref> On 18 October 2014, Tapine again played for the Junior Kiwis against the Junior Kangaroos, starting at second-row in the 15-14 win at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/2014-junior-kiwis-team-announced/|title=2014 JUNIOR KIWIS TEAM ANNOUNCED|publisher=Rugbyleagueweek.com.au|date=2014-10-10|accessdate=2015-03-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402092606/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/2014-junior-kiwis-team-announced/|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.warriors.co.nz/news/2014/10/18/junior_kiwis_confirm_line_up.html|title=Junior Kiwis confirm line-up|publisher=Warriors.co.nz|date=|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrl.co.nz/news-archive/taumalolo-added-to-train-on-squad.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927110620/http://www.nzrl.co.nz/news-archive/taumalolo-added-to-train-on-squad.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-09-27|title=Umbraco 4.5.1 - no pages found|publisher=Nzrl.co.nz|accessdate=2015-06-25}}</ref> On 24 November 2014, Tapine was charged with occasioning grievous bodily harm following an incident in September 2014 which left another man with a broken jaw.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-27/knights-player-charged-with-assault/5921108</ref>\n\n===2015===\nOn 23 June 2015, Tapine had assault charges dropped after a magistrate found prosecutors could not prove he was not acting in self-defence.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-23/assault-charges-dropped-against-knights-rookie-joseph-tapine/6566494</ref> In Round 22 against the [[Sydney Roosters]], Tapine scored his first NRL career try in the 38-22 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/knights/melbourne-storm-v-gold-coast-titans-newcastle-knights-v-sydney-roosters-live-coverage/news-story/9e828f8f1b362aebfe5908754c98e7e3</ref>Tapine improved on his previous season, playing in 13 matches and scoring 1 try in the [[2015 NRL season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTUtMTY2MC00LS0tLS0tMjA4MTctLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=2015-11-22|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref>[[File:Joseph Tapine.jpg|thumb|right|Tapine playing for the Newcastle Knights in the NSW Cup]] \nOn 27 September 2015, Tapine played in the Knights' [[2015 New South Wales Cup#Chart|2015 New South Wales Cup]] Grand Final against the [[Wyong Roos]] in the 20-10 victory at [[Parramatta Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nswrl.com.au/news/2015/09/22/vb_nsw_cup_grand_fin.html|title=VB NSW Cup Grand Final Team List|publisher=NSWRL|date=|accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Brett Keeble|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/newcastle-knights/newcastle-knights-extend-clint-newtons-career-with-nsw-cup-win-over-wyong-roos-20150927-gjw2gs.html|title=Newcastle Knights extend Clint Newton's career with NSW Cup win over Wyong Roos|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 11 February 2016, Tapine signed a 3-year contract with the [[Canberra Raiders]] starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/tapine-heads-to-canberra-on-monster-offer-20651/#toPq26vQv1OLyf7U.97|title=Tapine heads to Canberra on monster offer|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=2015-08-02|accessdate=2016-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Adrian Proszenko|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/joseph-tapine-tipped-to-leave-newcastle-immediately-after-signing-with-raiders-20160211-gmrjhy.html|title=Joseph Tapine tipped to leave Newcastle immediately after signing with Raiders|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2015-12-22|accessdate=2016-02-11}}</ref> After facing spending the year being banished from the Knights first grade squad to waste away in the NSW Cup, however, on 23 February 2017, the Knights agreed to release him from the remainder of his contract, freeing him to join the Raiders immediately.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/raiders-sign-joseph-tapine-20865/|title=Raiders sign Joseph Tapine|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=|accessdate=2016-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=39m ago|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/joseph-tapine-heading-to-canberra-raiders-after-standoff-with-newcastle-resolved-20160223-gn1f1k.html|title=Joseph Tapine heading to Canberra Raiders after standoff with Newcastle resolved|publisher=Canberratimes.com.au|date=2016-01-20|accessdate=2016-02-25}}</ref> In Round 3, Tapine made his club debut for the Canberra Raiders against the [[Newcastle Knights]], playing off the interchange bench in the 24-24 all draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/updated-round-3-nrl-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/93781/default.aspx|title=UPDATED: Round 3 NRL team lists|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref><ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/03/19/knights-raiders-play-out-thrilling-draw/</ref> In Round 12 against the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], Tapine scored his first and second club tries for the Raiders in the 32-20 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/live-nrl-canberra-raiders-v-canterburybankstown-bulldogs-scores-updates-news-blog/news-story/f83a05177f6f512df9e6b673da02bcff</ref> Tapine finished the [[2016 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 4 tries in his first year with the Canberra Raiders. On 4 October 2016, Tapine was selected in the [[New Zealand Kiwis]] 24-man squad for the [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016 Four Nations]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/10/04/2016-kangaroos-four-nations-squad/</ref> On 11 November 2016, Tapine made his international debut for the New Zealand Kiwis against [[Scotland national rugby league team|Scotland]], playing off the interchange bench in the shock 18-18 all draw at [[Derwent Park]].<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/scotland-managed-to-draw-with-new-zealand/news-story/c53915e3aa9d14e0b4f37de90173c84a</ref> Tapine played in 2 matches in the tournament including playing in the 2016 Four Nations Final match against [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]], off the interchange bench in the 34-8 loss at [[Anfield]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/four-nations-final-australia-hammer-new-zealand-348-20161121-gstkra.html</ref>\n\n===2017===\nTapine finished the [[2017 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries for the Raiders.<ref name=\"Joseph Tapine season review\">{{cite news|url=https://www.raiders.com.au/news/2017/10/24/joseph-tapine-season-review/|title=Joseph Tapine season review|publisher=NRL|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>  Tapine was named in the New Zealand Kiwis 24-man squad for the [[2017 Rugby League World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|date=5 October 2017|title=Kiwis World Cup squad named|url=http://www.nrl.com/kiwis-world-cup-squad-named/tabid/10874/newsid/113744/default.aspx|publisher=NRL|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> On 4 November, he scored his first international try for New Zealand against Scotland in the 74-6 smashing win at [[Christchurch Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11940530</ref> Tapine played in all 4 matches and scored 1 try in the Kiwis shock disappointing campaign.\n\n===2018===\nOn 24 June 2018, Tapine played for New Zealand against [[England national rugby league team|England]] in the historical test match set in [[Denver, USA]], starting at second-row in the 36-18 loss at [[Mile High Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/06/24/england-storm-home-to-beat-new-zealand-kiwis-in-denver-test/</ref> Tapine played in 16 matches and scored 6 tries for the Raiders in the [[2018 NRL season]].<ref name=\"NRL 2018: Raiders lose Joseph Tapine for rest of NRL season\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-2018-raiders-lose-joseph-tapine-for-rest-of-nrl-season/news-story/8c8ce93d0958eacaadd5f0bfe1a02c7d?from=rss-basic|title=NRL 2018: Raiders lose Joseph Tapine for rest of NRL season|publisher=News|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref> After being sidelined at the end of the year due to a broken thumb on 1 October 2018, Tapine was selected in the Kiwis 23-man squad for their tour of England and the test match against Australia.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/five-debutants-named-in-new-zealand-kiwis-squad-for-tests-against-australia-and-england/news-story/4fe2cb4b6b822599cb215409b46601b2</ref> Tapine played in 2 matches of the [[Baskerville Shield]] matches against England. On 24 October 2018, Tapine extended his contract with the Raiders for another 4-years, to the end of the 2023 season.<ref>https://www.theherald.com.au/story/5720536/raiders-retain-tapine-through-2023-season/</ref>\n\n===2019===\t\nOn 15 February, Tapine represented the [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|Maori All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] in the [[2019 All Stars match]], playing off the interchange bench in the 34-14 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/02/15/addo-carr-stars-as-indigenous-all-stars-beat-maori-all-stars/</ref>\n\nTapine made a total of 17 appearances for Canberra as the club reached the grand final for the first time in 25 years.  Tapine played at lock in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] as Canberra were defeated by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.raiders.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/canberra-raiders/joseph-tapine/ Canberra Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.raiders.com.au/team/profiles/joseph_tapine.html Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/2/playerid/5651/seasonid/44/default.aspx NRL profile]\n*[http://www.rlwc2017.com/players?team=377#Joseph-Tapine 2017 RLWC profile]\n\n{{Canberra Raiders squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2016 Four Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2017 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{2014 National Youth Competition Team of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tapine, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle Knights players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Junior Kiwis players]]\n[[Category:Wellington rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Mount Pritchard Mounties players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Joe Tapine\n|fullname       = Joseph Tapine\n|image          = Joe Tapine.jpg\n|imagesize      = 290\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1994|5|4}}\n|birth_place    = [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]\n|height         = {{convert|188|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|107|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|LK|SR}}\n|club1          = [[Newcastle Knights]]\n|year1start     = 2014\n|year1end       = 15\n|appearances1   = 20\n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 4\n|club2          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year2start     = 2016\n|year2end       = present\n|appearances2   = 80\n|tries2         = 14\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 56\n|teamA          = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearAstart     = 2016\n|yearAend       = present\n|appearancesA   = 9\n|triesA         = 2\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 8\n|teamB          = [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]]\t\n|yearBstart     = 2019\t\n|yearBend       =\n|appearancesB   = 1\n|triesB         = 0\n|goalsB         = 0\n|fieldgoalsB    = 0\n|pointsB        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/jospeh-tapine/summary.html|title=Joseph Tapine - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref><ref>[https://www.loverugbyleague.com/stats/players/Joseph-Tapine/ loverugbyleague]</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Tapine''' pronounced ({{IPAc-en|t|\u00e6|p|i\u02d0|n|\u025b}}) (born 4 May 1994), also known by the [[nickname]] of '''\"Joe\"''',<ref name=\"nrl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/knights-rookies-star-against-goannas/tabid/10874/newsid/76194/default.aspx|title=Knights rookies star against Goannas - NRL.com|publisher=nrl.com|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref> is a New Zealand professional [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|sr}} and {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. He has played for [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] and [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]] at international level. \n\nTapine previously played for the [[Newcastle Knights]] in the [[National Rugby League]]. \n\n==Background==\nTapine was born in [[Wellington]], New Zealand and is of M\u0101ori and Cook Island descent. \n\nTapine played his junior rugby league for the [[Harbour City Eagles]]. He then joined the [[Wellington rugby league team|Wellington Orcas]] in the [[New Zealand Rugby League]] [[National Competition]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early Career===\nIn 2013, Tapine joined the [[Newcastle Knights]] on a 1-year contract before re-signing for a further 3 years during the year.<ref name=\"newcastleknights2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/content/knights/club/members-only/knights_insider_wayne_bennett2.html|title=KNIGHTS INSIDER - Wayne Bennett - Knights|publisher=newcastleknights.com.au|accessdate=2014-07-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221312/http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/content/knights/club/members-only/knights_insider_wayne_bennett2.html|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref> He played for the Knights' [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team in 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://nycdatabase.org/players/t/|title=T|publisher=Nyc Database|date=|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> \nOn 13 October 2013, Tapine played for the [[Junior Kiwis]] against the [[Junior Kangaroos]], starting at second-row in the 38-26 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/nine-warriors-in-junior-kiwis-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/75024/default.aspx|title=Nine Warriors in Junior Kiwis squad|publisher=NRL.com|date=2013-10-08|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn Round 9 of the [[2014 NRL season]], Tapine made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the [[Newcastle Knights]] against the [[Penrith Panthers]], playing off the interchange bench in the 32-10 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/seasons/nrl-2014/round-9/newcastle-vs-penrith/summary.html|title=NRL 2014 - Round 9|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref><ref name=\"newcastleknights\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newcastleknights.com.au/news/2014/05/11/late_mail_knights_v_panthers.html|title=LATE MAIL: Knights v Panthers - Knights|publisher=newcastleknights.com.au|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref> Tapine finished off his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 7 matches for the Knights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTUtMTY0NC00LS0tLS0tMjA4MTctLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=2015-11-22|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref> On 2 September 2014, Tapine was named on the [[Rugby league positions#Interchange|interchange bench]] in the 2014 NYC Team of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/holden-team-year-announced/|title=Holden Cup Team Of The Year Announced|publisher=Rugbyleagueweek.com.au|date=2014-09-02|accessdate=2015-06-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626101814/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/holden-team-year-announced/|archivedate=2015-06-26}}</ref> On 18 October 2014, Tapine again played for the Junior Kiwis against the Junior Kangaroos, starting at second-row in the 15-14 win at [[Mt Smart Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/2014-junior-kiwis-team-announced/|title=2014 JUNIOR KIWIS TEAM ANNOUNCED|publisher=Rugbyleagueweek.com.au|date=2014-10-10|accessdate=2015-03-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402092606/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/2014-junior-kiwis-team-announced/|archivedate=2015-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.warriors.co.nz/news/2014/10/18/junior_kiwis_confirm_line_up.html|title=Junior Kiwis confirm line-up|publisher=Warriors.co.nz|date=|accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrl.co.nz/news-archive/taumalolo-added-to-train-on-squad.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927110620/http://www.nzrl.co.nz/news-archive/taumalolo-added-to-train-on-squad.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-09-27|title=Umbraco 4.5.1 - no pages found|publisher=Nzrl.co.nz|accessdate=2015-06-25}}</ref> On 24 November 2014, Tapine was charged with occasioning grievous bodily harm following an incident in September 2014 which left another man with a broken jaw.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-27/knights-player-charged-with-assault/5921108</ref>\n\n===2015===\nOn 23 June 2015, Tapine had assault charges dropped after a magistrate found prosecutors could not prove he was not acting in self-defence.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-06-23/assault-charges-dropped-against-knights-rookie-joseph-tapine/6566494</ref> In Round 22 against the [[Sydney Roosters]], Tapine scored his first NRL career try in the 38-22 loss at [[Hunter Stadium]].<ref>https://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/knights/melbourne-storm-v-gold-coast-titans-newcastle-knights-v-sydney-roosters-live-coverage/news-story/9e828f8f1b362aebfe5908754c98e7e3</ref>Tapine improved on his previous season, playing in 13 matches and scoring 1 try in the [[2015 NRL season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/matches/Custom/MTUtMTY2MC00LS0tLS0tMjA4MTctLS0tLS0tLS0tLS0t|title=Custom Match List|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=2015-11-22|accessdate=2016-01-11}}</ref>[[File:Joseph Tapine.jpg|thumb|right|Tapine playing for the Newcastle Knights in the NSW Cup]] \nOn 27 September 2015, Tapine played in the Knights' [[2015 New South Wales Cup#Chart|2015 New South Wales Cup]] Grand Final against the [[Wyong Roos]] in the 20-10 victory at [[Parramatta Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nswrl.com.au/news/2015/09/22/vb_nsw_cup_grand_fin.html|title=VB NSW Cup Grand Final Team List|publisher=NSWRL|date=|accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Brett Keeble|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/newcastle-knights/newcastle-knights-extend-clint-newtons-career-with-nsw-cup-win-over-wyong-roos-20150927-gjw2gs.html|title=Newcastle Knights extend Clint Newton's career with NSW Cup win over Wyong Roos|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-10-15}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn 11 February 2016, Tapine signed a 3-year contract with the [[Canberra Raiders]] starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/tapine-heads-to-canberra-on-monster-offer-20651/#toPq26vQv1OLyf7U.97|title=Tapine heads to Canberra on monster offer|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=2015-08-02|accessdate=2016-02-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Adrian Proszenko|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/joseph-tapine-tipped-to-leave-newcastle-immediately-after-signing-with-raiders-20160211-gmrjhy.html|title=Joseph Tapine tipped to leave Newcastle immediately after signing with Raiders|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2015-12-22|accessdate=2016-02-11}}</ref> After facing spending the year being banished from the Knights first grade squad to waste away in the NSW Cup, however, on 23 February 2017, the Knights agreed to release him from the remainder of his contract, freeing him to join the Raiders immediately.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/raiders-sign-joseph-tapine-20865/|title=Raiders sign Joseph Tapine|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=|accessdate=2016-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=39m ago|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/joseph-tapine-heading-to-canberra-raiders-after-standoff-with-newcastle-resolved-20160223-gn1f1k.html|title=Joseph Tapine heading to Canberra Raiders after standoff with Newcastle resolved|publisher=Canberratimes.com.au|date=2016-01-20|accessdate=2016-02-25}}</ref> In Round 3, Tapine made his club debut for the Canberra Raiders against the [[Newcastle Knights]], playing off the interchange bench in the 24-24 all draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/updated-round-3-nrl-team-lists/tabid/10874/newsid/93781/default.aspx|title=UPDATED: Round 3 NRL team lists|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2016-03-20}}</ref><ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/03/19/knights-raiders-play-out-thrilling-draw/</ref> In Round 12 against the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], Tapine scored his first and second club tries for the Raiders in the 32-20 win at [[Canberra Stadium]].<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/live-nrl-canberra-raiders-v-canterburybankstown-bulldogs-scores-updates-news-blog/news-story/f83a05177f6f512df9e6b673da02bcff</ref> Tapine finished the [[2016 NRL season]] with him playing in 25 matches and scoring 4 tries in his first year with the Canberra Raiders. On 4 October 2016, Tapine was selected in the [[New Zealand Kiwis]] 24-man squad for the [[2016 Rugby League Four Nations|2016 Four Nations]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2016/10/04/2016-kangaroos-four-nations-squad/</ref> On 11 November 2016, Tapine made his international debut for the New Zealand Kiwis against [[Scotland national rugby league team|Scotland]], playing off the interchange bench in the shock 18-18 all draw at [[Derwent Park]].<ref>https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/scotland-managed-to-draw-with-new-zealand/news-story/c53915e3aa9d14e0b4f37de90173c84a</ref> Tapine played in 2 matches in the tournament including playing in the 2016 Four Nations Final match against [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]], off the interchange bench in the 34-8 loss at [[Anfield]].<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/four-nations-final-australia-hammer-new-zealand-348-20161121-gstkra.html</ref>\n\n===2017===\nTapine finished the [[2017 NRL season]] with him playing in 22 matches and scoring 3 tries for the Raiders.<ref name=\"Joseph Tapine season review\">{{cite news|url=https://www.raiders.com.au/news/2017/10/24/joseph-tapine-season-review/|title=Joseph Tapine season review|publisher=NRL|date=24 October 2017|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref>  Tapine was named in the New Zealand Kiwis 24-man squad for the [[2017 Rugby League World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|date=5 October 2017|title=Kiwis World Cup squad named|url=http://www.nrl.com/kiwis-world-cup-squad-named/tabid/10874/newsid/113744/default.aspx|publisher=NRL|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> On 4 November, he scored his first international try for New Zealand against Scotland in the 74-6 smashing win at [[Christchurch Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11940530</ref> Tapine played in all 4 matches and scored 1 try in the Kiwis shock disappointing campaign.\n\n===2018===\nOn 24 June 2018, Tapine played for New Zealand against [[England national rugby league team|England]] in the historical test match set in [[Denver, USA]], starting at second-row in the 36-18 loss at [[Mile High Stadium]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2018/06/24/england-storm-home-to-beat-new-zealand-kiwis-in-denver-test/</ref> Tapine played in 16 matches and scored 6 tries for the Raiders in the [[2018 NRL season]].<ref name=\"NRL 2018: Raiders lose Joseph Tapine for rest of NRL season\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-2018-raiders-lose-joseph-tapine-for-rest-of-nrl-season/news-story/8c8ce93d0958eacaadd5f0bfe1a02c7d?from=rss-basic|title=NRL 2018: Raiders lose Joseph Tapine for rest of NRL season|publisher=News|date=21 August 2018|accessdate=11 November 2018}}</ref> After being sidelined at the end of the year due to a broken thumb on 1 October 2018, Tapine was selected in the Kiwis 23-man squad for their tour of England and the test match against Australia.<ref>https://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/five-debutants-named-in-new-zealand-kiwis-squad-for-tests-against-australia-and-england/news-story/4fe2cb4b6b822599cb215409b46601b2</ref> Tapine played in 2 matches of the [[Baskerville Shield]] matches against England. On 24 October 2018, Tapine extended his contract with the Raiders for another 4-years, to the end of the 2023 season.<ref>https://www.theherald.com.au/story/5720536/raiders-retain-tapine-through-2023-season/</ref>\n\n===2019===\t\nOn 15 February, Tapine represented the [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team|Maori All Stars]] against the [[Indigenous All Stars (rugby league)|Indigenous All Stars]] in the [[2019 All Stars match]], playing off the interchange bench in the 34-14 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/2019/02/15/addo-carr-stars-as-indigenous-all-stars-beat-maori-all-stars/</ref>\n\nTapine made a total of 17 appearances for Canberra as the club reached the grand final for the first time in 25 years.  Tapine played at lock in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] as Canberra were defeated by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.raiders.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/canberra-raiders/joseph-tapine/ Canberra Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.raiders.com.au/team/profiles/joseph_tapine.html Raiders profile]\n*[http://www.nrl.com/telstrapremiership/playerstats/playerprofile/tabid/10898/clubid/2/playerid/5651/seasonid/44/default.aspx NRL profile]\n*[http://www.rlwc2017.com/players?team=377#Joseph-Tapine 2017 RLWC profile]\n\n{{Canberra Raiders squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2016 Four Nations squad}}\n{{New Zealand 2017 Rugby League World Cup squad}}\n{{2014 National Youth Competition Team of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tapine, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle Knights players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Junior Kiwis players]]\n[[Category:Wellington rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Mount Pritchard Mounties players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bbatt42", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Tapine"}
{"title_page": "Kevin S. Huffman", "text_new": "'''Kevin S. Huffman''' (born September 22, 1970) is an American lawyer and education administrator who was the Commissioner of the [[Tennessee Department of Education]]. He was appointed to the position by Tennessee Governor [[Bill Haslam]] and served from April 2011 to January 2015.<ref name=TDOE>{{cite web|url=http://www.tn.gov/education/AboutCommissioner.shtml |title=About the Commissioner|publisher=Tennessee Department of Education}}</ref> Prior to his work at the Tennessee Department of Education, Huffman held a senior management position in Teach for America and had worked as an attorney specializing in education.<ref name=knoxnewstapped>{{cite news|url=http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2011/mar/03/kevin-huffman-of-teach-for-america-tapped-to-be/ |title=Kevin Huffman of Teach for America tapped to be new state education chief |publisher=knoxnews.com |date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHuffman resigned as Tennessee Commissioner of Education on November 13, 2014, noting that he has plans to work as a private consultant and plans to continue living in Nashville.<ref name=tennessean>{{cite news|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2014/11/13/kevin-huffman-out-as-tennessee-commissioner-of-education/18977281/\n |title= Kevin Huffman out as education commissioner |publisher=tennessean.com |date=November 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHuffman graduated from [[Bexley High School]] in [[Bexley, Ohio]], in 1988.<ref name=Bexley/> He then attended [[Swarthmore College]], receiving a B.A. in English literature in 1992.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nHe began his career in education after graduation, becoming a [[Teach For America]] corps member in [[Houston, Texas]]. He taught bilingual first- and second-grade students in English and Spanish for the Houston Independent School District. He was a member of his school's elected shared-decision making committee, and trained new teachers as a faculty advisor and school director at Teach For America's summer training institutes.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nAfter finishing his assignment as a teacher for Teach for America, Huffman attended [[New York University School of Law]], where he was a member of the law review and graduated in 1998.  After law school, he joined the Washington, DC, law firm of [[Hogan & Hartson]], where he represented school districts, state departments of education and universities, and worked on policy and litigation matters including challenges to state finance systems, desegregation litigation, and [[special education]] hearings and trials.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nIn 2000, Huffman became a staff member for Teach For America. In more than a decade with that organization, he served as general counsel, senior vice president of growth strategy and development, and executive vice president of public affairs.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nIn 2009, Huffman was voted \"America's Next Great Pundit\" by [[The Washington Post]], where he had an opinion column from 2009 to 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://views.washingtonpost.com/pundit-judges/2009/11/angp_winner_kevin_huffman.html |title=America's Next Great Pundit Contest |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/linkset/2009/12/10/LI2009121002695.html |title=Kevin Huffman, Opinion Writer |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, [[Tennessee Governor]] [[Bill Haslam]] announced that he was appointing Huffman to head the state's Department of Education. Huffman started work in April 2011.<ref name=\"TDOE\"/> He was the first Teach For America participant to assume the leadership of a state's public education program.<ref name=Bexley>{{cite web|url=http://www.bexleyalumni.org/FeaturesArticles/KevinHuffman.htm| publisher=Bexley High School Alumni Association |title=Bexley Alum Named to Office}}</ref>\n\nIn his first months as head of the Tennessee Department of Education, Huffman oversaw the implementation of a new evaluation system for teachers and [[school principal]]s that seeks to provide a comprehensive look at educator performance based on multiple measures of effectiveness, including classroom observations, student academic growth, and locally selected measures of student achievement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/sep/29/governor-education-commissioner-defend-teacher/ |title=Governor Haslam, Tennessee education commissioner defend teacher evaluation system |author=Andy Sher |date=September 29, 2011 |newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press}}</ref><ref name=TimesFreePressJan13>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2013/jan/13/education-reformer-has-interest-in-state/ |title=Education reformer has interest in Tennessee |author=Andy Sher |date=January 13, 2013 |newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press}}</ref> He has called the evaluation system, which requires targeted feedback for teachers, \"a model for the rest of the country.\"<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/>\n\nAlso in his time at the Tennessee Department of Education, Tennessee became one of the first states receive a waiver from the Federal [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] (ESEA) (also known as [[No Child Left Behind]]), and he continued the focus on higher college- and career-ready standards through the Tennessee Diploma Project and the [[Common Core State Standards Initiative]].<ref name=\"TDOE\"/><ref name=\"U.S. Department of Education\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/policy/elsec/guid/esea-flexibility/map/tn.html |title=Tennessee ESEA Flexibility Request |publisher=U.S. Department of Education}}</ref>\n\nHuffman was also instrumental in creating the state's [[Achievement School District]] (ASD), which aims to move the bottom 5% of school in TN to the top 25% by 2018.<ref name=\"Achievement School District\">{{cite web|url=http://achievementschooldistrict.org/ |title=Achievement School District Home Page |publisher=Achievement School District}}</ref> In its first year, the ASD saw a drop in reading proficiency but also saw improvements in both math and science achievement.<ref name=\"Memphis Daily News\">{{cite news|url=http://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2013/jul/24/achievement-school-district-tcaps-reading-down-math-and-science-up/ |title=Achievement School District TCAPs: Reading Down, Math and Science Up |author=Bill Dries |date=July 24, 2013 |newspaper=Memphis Daily News}}</ref>\n\nUnder his tenure, Tennessee saw the largest academic gains in a single testing cycle since the [[National Assessment of Educational Progress]] (NAEP) started nationwide assessments a decade ago, along with impressive gains for [[African American]] students.<ref name=\"Tennessee Students The Fastest Improving In The Nation\">{{cite web|url=https://news.tn.gov/node/11644 |title=Tennessee Students The Fastest Improving In The Nation |publisher=Tennessee Newsroom}}</ref><ref name=\"National Center for Education Statistics\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov |title=National Center for Education Statistics |publisher=U.S. Department of Education}}</ref> Additionally, from 2009-2013, the number of [[ACT test]]-taking graduates increased by 33.8%, while the number of graduates in Tennessee decreased by 2.2%.<ref name=\"The Condition of College & Career Readiness 2013: Tennessee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.act.org/newsroom/data/2013/states/pdf/Tennessee.pdf |title=The Condition of College & Career Readiness 2013: Tennessee |publisher=ACT}}</ref>\n\nHis time as Commissioner was not without controversy - in September 2012, he ordered that $3.4 million in state funding be withheld from [[Metropolitan Nashville Public Schools]] after its school board refused to authorize a proposed [[Great Hearts Academies]] charter school in West Nashville.<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tennessean.com/article/20130228/NEWS04/302280045/TN-Education-Commissioner-Kevin-Huffman-says-charters-can-serve-better |title=TN Education Commissioner Kevin Huffman says charters can serve better |date=Feb 28, 2013 |author=Lisa Fingeroot |newspaper=The Tennessean |location=Nashville}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/great-hearts-how-charter-operator-lost-political-fallout-and-what-happens-now |title=Great Hearts: How charter operator lost, the political fallout and what happens now |author=Joey Garrison |newspaper=Nashville City Paper |date=September 23, 2012}}</ref> In September 2013, a petition was sent to the governor, signed by 55 of the states' [[school superintendent|school director]]s, alleging that Huffman was not responsive to local school officials and had contributed to low teacher morale and other problems.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nAs an advocate of [[charter schools]], Huffman oversaw an increase from 29 public charter schools when he took office to 71 schools in the 2013-2014 school year.<ref name=\"The Public Charter Schools Dashboard\">{{cite web|url=http://dashboard.publiccharters.org/dashboard/schools/page/overview/state/TN/year/2014 |title=Tennessee Public Charter Schools Dashboard |publisher=National Alliance for Public Charter Schools}}</ref> In December 2014, Tennessee was ranked 2nd of 17 states for its charter school policy environment that promotes both quality and accountability.<ref name=\"Tennessee State Policy Report\">{{cite web|url=http://www.qualitycharters.org/assets/files/images/State_Policy_Report/TN.pdf |title=Tennessee State Policy Report |publisher=National Association of Charter School Authorizers}}</ref>\n\nHuffman also oversaw consistently improved student achievement on the state's annual [[Tennessee Comprehensive Assessment Program]] (TCAP). As of 2014, nearly 50 percent of Algebra II students were on grade level, an improvement from 31 percent in 2011. Additionally, achievement gaps for minority students narrowed in math and reading at both the 3-8 and high school levels.<ref name=\"2014 TCAP State Results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tn.gov/education/data/tcap_2014.shtml |title=2014 TCAP State Results |publisher=TDOE}}</ref> He also led efforts to create a differentiated compensation system for educators in Tennessee. This system gives local districts more control and flexibility over their pay systems, allowing them to address and reward teachers for their various roles and contributions.<ref name=\"Tennessee Differentiated Pay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessee.gov/education/districts/pay.shtml |title=Tennessee Differentiated Pay |publisher=TDOE}}</ref> Huffman also created a structure to provide more than 30,000 Tennessee educators with insight and training on teaching the Common Core State Standards.<ref name=\"Tennessee Trains 30,000 Teachers in the Common Core State Standards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.gov/edblogs/progress/2013/12/tennessee-trains-more-than-30000-teachers-in-the-common-core-state-standards/ |title=Tennessee Trains 30,000 Teachers in the Common Core State Standards |publisher=U.S. Department of Education, Progress Blog}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nWhile teaching, Huffman met fellow Teach for America Corps member [[Michelle Rhee]].<ref name=TimeRheeTackles>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1862444-2,00.html |title=Rhee Tackles Classroom Challenge |author=Amanda Ripley |date= November 26, 2008 |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> The couple married two years after they met and had two daughters before they divorced in 2007.<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/><ref name=TimeRheeTackles/>\n\nHuffman and his second wife, Amy, have one child, Asher, and at the time of Huffman\u2019s resignation were expecting a second.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huffman, Kevin S.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American school administrators]]\n[[Category:Education in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Teach For America alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kevin S. Huffman''' (born September 22, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] lawyer and education administrator who was the Commissioner of the [[Tennessee Department of Education]]. He was appointed to the position by Tennessee Governor [[Bill Haslam]] and served from April 2011 to January 2015.<ref name=TDOE>{{cite web|url=http://www.tn.gov/education/AboutCommissioner.shtml |title=About the Commissioner|publisher=Tennessee Department of Education}}</ref> Prior to his work at the Tennessee Department of Education, Huffman held a senior management position in Teach for America and had worked as an attorney specializing in education.<ref name=knoxnewstapped>{{cite news|url=http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2011/mar/03/kevin-huffman-of-teach-for-america-tapped-to-be/ |title=Kevin Huffman of Teach for America tapped to be new state education chief |publisher=knoxnews.com |date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHuffman resigned as Tennessee Commissioner of Education on November 13, 2014, noting that he has plans to work as a private consultant and plans to continue living in Nashville.<ref name=tennessean>{{cite news|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2014/11/13/kevin-huffman-out-as-tennessee-commissioner-of-education/18977281/\n |title= Kevin Huffman out as education commissioner |publisher=tennessean.com |date=November 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHuffman graduated from [[Bexley High School]] in [[Bexley, Ohio]], in 1988.<ref name=Bexley/> He then attended [[Swarthmore College]], receiving a B.A. in English literature in 1992.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nHe began his career in education after graduation, becoming a [[Teach For America]] corps member in [[Houston, Texas]]. He taught bilingual first- and second-grade students in English and Spanish for the Houston Independent School District. He was a member of his school's elected shared-decision making committee, and trained new teachers as a faculty advisor and school director at Teach For America's summer training institutes.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nAfter finishing his assignment as a teacher for Teach for America, Huffman attended [[New York University School of Law]], where he was a member of the law review and graduated in 1998.  After law school, he joined the Washington, DC, law firm of [[Hogan & Hartson]], where he represented school districts, state departments of education and universities, and worked on policy and litigation matters including challenges to state finance systems, desegregation litigation, and [[special education]] hearings and trials.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nIn 2000, Huffman became a staff member for Teach For America. In more than a decade with that organization, he served as general counsel, senior vice president of growth strategy and development, and executive vice president of public affairs.<ref name=TDOE/>\n\nIn 2009, Huffman was voted \"America's Next Great Pundit\" by [[The Washington Post]], where he had an opinion column from 2009 to 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://views.washingtonpost.com/pundit-judges/2009/11/angp_winner_kevin_huffman.html |title=America's Next Great Pundit Contest |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/linkset/2009/12/10/LI2009121002695.html |title=Kevin Huffman, Opinion Writer |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, [[Tennessee Governor]] [[Bill Haslam]] announced that he was appointing Huffman to head the state's Department of Education. Huffman started work in April 2011.<ref name=\"TDOE\"/> He was the first Teach For America participant to assume the leadership of a state's public education program.<ref name=Bexley>{{cite web|url=http://www.bexleyalumni.org/FeaturesArticles/KevinHuffman.htm| publisher=Bexley High School Alumni Association |title=Bexley Alum Named to Office}}</ref>\n\nIn his first months as head of the Tennessee Department of Education, Huffman oversaw the implementation of a new evaluation system for teachers and [[school principal]]s that seeks to provide a comprehensive look at educator performance based on multiple measures of effectiveness, including classroom observations, student academic growth, and locally selected measures of student achievement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/sep/29/governor-education-commissioner-defend-teacher/ |title=Governor Haslam, Tennessee education commissioner defend teacher evaluation system |author=Andy Sher |date=September 29, 2011 |newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press}}</ref><ref name=TimesFreePressJan13>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2013/jan/13/education-reformer-has-interest-in-state/ |title=Education reformer has interest in Tennessee |author=Andy Sher |date=January 13, 2013 |newspaper=Chattanooga Times Free Press}}</ref> He has called the evaluation system, which requires targeted feedback for teachers, \"a model for the rest of the country.\"<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/>\n\nAlso in his time at the Tennessee Department of Education, Tennessee became one of the first states receive a waiver from the Federal [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] (ESEA) (also known as [[No Child Left Behind]]), and he continued the focus on higher college- and career-ready standards through the Tennessee Diploma Project and the [[Common Core State Standards Initiative]].<ref name=\"TDOE\"/><ref name=\"U.S. Department of Education\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/policy/elsec/guid/esea-flexibility/map/tn.html |title=Tennessee ESEA Flexibility Request |publisher=U.S. Department of Education}}</ref>\n\nHuffman was also instrumental in creating the state's [[Achievement School District]] (ASD), which aims to move the bottom 5% of school in TN to the top 25% by 2018.<ref name=\"Achievement School District\">{{cite web|url=http://achievementschooldistrict.org/ |title=Achievement School District Home Page |publisher=Achievement School District}}</ref> In its first year, the ASD saw a drop in reading proficiency but also saw improvements in both math and science achievement.<ref name=\"Memphis Daily News\">{{cite news|url=http://www.memphisdailynews.com/news/2013/jul/24/achievement-school-district-tcaps-reading-down-math-and-science-up/ |title=Achievement School District TCAPs: Reading Down, Math and Science Up |author=Bill Dries |date=July 24, 2013 |newspaper=Memphis Daily News}}</ref>\n\nUnder his tenure, Tennessee saw the largest academic gains in a single testing cycle since the [[National Assessment of Educational Progress]] (NAEP) started nationwide assessments a decade ago, along with impressive gains for [[African American]] students.<ref name=\"Tennessee Students The Fastest Improving In The Nation\">{{cite web|url=https://news.tn.gov/node/11644 |title=Tennessee Students The Fastest Improving In The Nation |publisher=Tennessee Newsroom}}</ref><ref name=\"National Center for Education Statistics\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov |title=National Center for Education Statistics |publisher=U.S. Department of Education}}</ref> Additionally, from 2009-2013, the number of [[ACT test]]-taking graduates increased by 33.8%, while the number of graduates in Tennessee decreased by 2.2%.<ref name=\"The Condition of College & Career Readiness 2013: Tennessee\">{{cite web|url=http://www.act.org/newsroom/data/2013/states/pdf/Tennessee.pdf |title=The Condition of College & Career Readiness 2013: Tennessee |publisher=ACT}}</ref>\n\nHis time as Commissioner was not without controversy - in September 2012, he ordered that $3.4 million in state funding be withheld from [[Metropolitan Nashville Public Schools]] after its school board refused to authorize a proposed [[Great Hearts Academies]] charter school in West Nashville.<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tennessean.com/article/20130228/NEWS04/302280045/TN-Education-Commissioner-Kevin-Huffman-says-charters-can-serve-better |title=TN Education Commissioner Kevin Huffman says charters can serve better |date=Feb 28, 2013 |author=Lisa Fingeroot |newspaper=The Tennessean |location=Nashville}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/great-hearts-how-charter-operator-lost-political-fallout-and-what-happens-now |title=Great Hearts: How charter operator lost, the political fallout and what happens now |author=Joey Garrison |newspaper=Nashville City Paper |date=September 23, 2012}}</ref> In September 2013, a petition was sent to the governor, signed by 55 of the states' [[school superintendent|school director]]s, alleging that Huffman was not responsive to local school officials and had contributed to low teacher morale and other problems.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nAs an advocate of [[charter schools]], Huffman oversaw an increase from 29 public charter schools when he took office to 71 schools in the 2013-2014 school year.<ref name=\"The Public Charter Schools Dashboard\">{{cite web|url=http://dashboard.publiccharters.org/dashboard/schools/page/overview/state/TN/year/2014 |title=Tennessee Public Charter Schools Dashboard |publisher=National Alliance for Public Charter Schools}}</ref> In December 2014, Tennessee was ranked 2nd of 17 states for its charter school policy environment that promotes both quality and accountability.<ref name=\"Tennessee State Policy Report\">{{cite web|url=http://www.qualitycharters.org/assets/files/images/State_Policy_Report/TN.pdf |title=Tennessee State Policy Report |publisher=National Association of Charter School Authorizers}}</ref>\n\nHuffman also oversaw consistently improved student achievement on the state's annual [[Tennessee Comprehensive Assessment Program]] (TCAP). As of 2014, nearly 50 percent of Algebra II students were on grade level, an improvement from 31 percent in 2011. Additionally, achievement gaps for minority students narrowed in math and reading at both the 3-8 and high school levels.<ref name=\"2014 TCAP State Results\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tn.gov/education/data/tcap_2014.shtml |title=2014 TCAP State Results |publisher=TDOE}}</ref> He also led efforts to create a differentiated compensation system for educators in Tennessee. This system gives local districts more control and flexibility over their pay systems, allowing them to address and reward teachers for their various roles and contributions.<ref name=\"Tennessee Differentiated Pay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessee.gov/education/districts/pay.shtml |title=Tennessee Differentiated Pay |publisher=TDOE}}</ref> Huffman also created a structure to provide more than 30,000 Tennessee educators with insight and training on teaching the Common Core State Standards.<ref name=\"Tennessee Trains 30,000 Teachers in the Common Core State Standards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.gov/edblogs/progress/2013/12/tennessee-trains-more-than-30000-teachers-in-the-common-core-state-standards/ |title=Tennessee Trains 30,000 Teachers in the Common Core State Standards |publisher=U.S. Department of Education, Progress Blog}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nWhile teaching, Huffman met fellow Teach for America Corps member [[Michelle Rhee]].<ref name=TimeRheeTackles>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1862444-2,00.html |title=Rhee Tackles Classroom Challenge |author=Amanda Ripley |date= November 26, 2008 |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> The couple married two years after they met and had two daughters before they divorced in 2007.<ref name=TimesFreePressJan13/><ref name=TimeRheeTackles/>\n\nHuffman and his second wife, Amy, have one child, Asher, and at the time of Huffman\u2019s resignation were expecting a second.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huffman, Kevin S.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American school administrators]]\n[[Category:Education in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:New York University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:State cabinet secretaries of Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Teach For America alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:OVERLINK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_S._Huffman"}
{"title_page": "Dunamis Lui", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Nami Lui\n|fullname       = Dunamis Lui\n|nickname       = Nami<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Nami_Lui|title=Dunamis Lui (@Nami_Lui)|publisher=Twitter|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n|image          = Dunamis Lui.jpg\n|imagesize      = 150\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|02|16}}\n|birth_place    = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n|height         = {{convert|180|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|104|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|PR|LK|SR}}\n|club1          = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year1start     = 2010\n|year1end       = 13\n|appearances1   = 32\n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 4\n|club2          = [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly Sea Eagles]]\n|year2start     = 2014\n|year2end       = 15\n|appearances2   = 38\n|tries2         = 1\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 4\n|club3          = [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]]\n|year3start     = 2016\n|year3end       = \n|appearances3   = 10\n|tries3         = 0\n|goals3         = 0\n|fieldgoals3    = 0\n|points3        = 0\n|club4          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year4start     = 2017\n|year4end       = present\n|appearances4   = 60\n|tries4         = 1\n|goals4         = 0\n|fieldgoals4    = 0\n|points4        = 4\n|teamA          = [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]]\n|yearAstart     = 2014\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 6\n|triesA         = 0\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/dunamis-lui/summary.html|title=Dunamis Lui - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Dunamis Lui''' (born 16 February 1990) is a [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] international [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|pr|sr}} and {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. \n\nHe previously played for the [[Brisbane Broncos]], [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles]] and the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]].\n\n==Background==\nLui was born in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Queensland]], Australia. He is of [[Samoan people|Samoan descent]].\n\nLui played his junior football for the [[Aspley Broncos|Aspley Devils]] and [[Past Brothers|Brisbane Brothers]] before being signed by the [[Brisbane Broncos]]. \n[[File:dunamislui.jpg|thumb|right|Lui playing for the Broncos in 2009]]\nLui played for the Broncos [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team from 2008 to 2010.<ref>[http://rleague.com/players/Dunamis-Lui_2094/Matches/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906192941/http://rleague.com/players/Dunamis-Lui_2094/Matches/|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> Lui has played for the Queensland Schoolboys team. Lui has played for the AIS team.\n\n==Playing career==\n===2010===\nIn round 5 of the [[2010 NRL season]], Lui made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] against the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] off the interchange bench in the Broncos 34-16 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-name-dunamis-lui-in-nrl-squad-for-dragons-clash/story-e6frep5x-1225850485474|title=Broncos Name Dunamis Lui in NRL Squad for Dragons Clash|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-v-brisbane-broncos-at-win-stadium/story-e6frep5x-1225851911501|title=Dragons v Broncos at Win Stadium|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In round 6 against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], Lui scored his first NRL career try in the Broncos 44-16 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Wayne Heming|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/broncos-punish-gummy-sharks-20100418-smah.html|title=Broncos punish gummy Sharks|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2010-04-18|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 4 matches and scoring a try for the [[Brisbane Broncos]].\n\n===2011===\nOn 12 May 2011, Lui re-signed with Brisbane on a two-year contract to the end of the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8248364|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130730075833/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8248364|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-07-30|title=Broncos sign two more young NRL hopefuls|publisher=Wwos.ninemsn.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished the [[2011 NRL season]] with him playing in 6 matches for the Broncos.\n\n===2012===\nLui finished the [[2012 NRL season]] with him played in 9 matches for Brisbane.\n\n===2013===\nOn 28 August 2013, Lui signed a one-year contract with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] starting in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/brisbane-prop-dunamis-lui-poised-to-leave-broncos-to-join-manly-sea-eagles-or-cronulla-sharks/story-fni3gv5x-1226705224909|title=Dunamis Lui Poised to Leave Broncos|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seaeagles.com.au/news-display/eagles/86013 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019011536/http://www.seaeagles.com.au/news-display/eagles/86013|date=19 October 2013}}</ref> Lui played in 13 matches in his last year for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[2013 NRL season]].\n\n===2014===\nIn round 1 of the [[2014 NRL season]], Lui made his club debut for the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]] off the interchange bench in the club's 23-22 loss at [[Brookvale Oval]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/anthony-watmough-has-declared-his-sides-performance-on-the-weekend-as-not-up-to-nrl-standard/story-e6frf3ru-1226851929219|title=Anthony Watmough Has Declared His Side's Performance as Not up to NRL Standard|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2014, Lui played for [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] in the [[Pacific Rugby League International#2014 test|2014 Pacific Rugby League International]] against [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]] off the interchange bench in Samoa's 32-16 win at [[Penrith Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/gutsy-samoa-secures-place-in-four-nations-tournament-following-win-over-fiji/story-fni3fbgz-1226904268873|title=Gutsy Samoa Secures Place in Four Nations Tournament|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In round 17 against the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], Lui scored his first club try for Manly-Warringah in the 23-16 loss at [[ANZ Stadium]], Lui scoring his first try since round 6 of the [[2010 NRL season]] for the [[Brisbane Broncos]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Sonter|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/rugby-league-match-centre/live-bulldogs-v-sea-eagles-20140704-3bdjf.html|title=Live: Bulldogs v Sea Eagles|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2014-07-04|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished off his first year with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] with him playing in 21 matches and scoring a try in the [[2014 NRL season]]. On 7 October 2014, Lui was selected in [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] 24-man squad for the [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/toa-samoa-name-four-nations-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/82434/default.aspx|title=Toa Samoa name Four Nations squad|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui played in 2 matches in the tournament.\n\n===2015===\nOn 23 January, Lui was named in Manly's [[2015 Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/sea-eagles-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|title=SEA EAGLES UNVEIL 2015 NINES SQUAD|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2015-01-23|accessdate=2015-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716054235/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/sea-eagles-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|archive-date=16 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 2 May, Lui played for [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] in the 2015 [[Pacific Rugby League International#Polynesian Cup|Polynesian Cup]] battle against [[Tonga national rugby league team|Tonga]], playing off the interchange bench in Samoa's 18-16 win at [[Cbus Super Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/video-sam-kasiano-try-saving-tackle-on-jorge-taufua-secures-pacific-test-win-for-samoan-against-tonga/story-e6frf3ou-1227331678892|title=Video|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> On 16 September, Lui signed a two-year contract with [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] starting in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/dragons-sign-dunamis-lui/tabid/10874/newsid/89857/default.aspx|title=Dragons sign Sea Eagles forward|publisher=NRL.com|date=2015-09-16|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/nrl/dragons-sign-dunamis-lui-19036/|title=Dragons sign Dunamis Lui &#124; NRL|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished his last year with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] with him playing in 17 matches in the [[2015 NRL season]].\n\n===2016===\nIn February, Lui played for [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] in the [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/dragons-name-2016-nines-squad/|title=Dragons name 2016 Nines squad|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2016-01-29|accessdate=2016-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204025959/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/dragons-name-2016-nines-squad/|archive-date=4 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In round 1 of the [[2016 NRL season]], Lui made his club debut for [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]], playing off the interchange bench in St. George's 18-16 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/storm/melbourne-storm-defeat-the-dragons-1816-at-aami-park/news-story/3f45ed468af51012df6c60a6182d7d86</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2016, Lui signed a two-year deal with the [[Canberra Raiders]] commencing in 2017.\n\n===2018===\nLui signed a further three-year extension on August 8, 2018, keeping him at the [[Canberra Raiders]] until the end of the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/dunamis-lui-pens-canberra-raiders-extension-20180808-p4zw5s.html|title=Dunamis Lui pens Canberra Raiders extension|first=Caden|last=Helmers|date=8 August 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nLui made 27 appearances for Canberra in the [[2019 NRL season]] as the club reached their first grand final in 25 years.  Lui played from the bench in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] in which Canberra were defeated by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.raiders.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/canberra-raiders/dunamis-lui/ Canberra Raiders profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151224053358/http://www.dragons.com.au/team/profiles/dunamis_lui.html St. George Illawarra Dragons profile]\n\n{{Canberra Raiders squad}}\n{{Samoa 2014 Rugby League Four Nations squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lui, Dunamis}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Samoan descent]]\n[[Category:Samoa national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Samoan rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Manly Warringah Sea Eagles players]]\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Norths Devils players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league props]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Brisbane]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name           = Nami Lui\n|fullname       = Dunamis Lui\n|nickname       = Nami<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Nami_Lui|title=Dunamis Lui (@Nami_Lui)|publisher=Twitter|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n|image          = Dunamis Lui.jpg\n|imagesize      = 150\n|caption        = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|02|16}}\n|birth_place    = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n|height         = {{convert|180|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|weight         = {{convert|104|kg|stlb|abbr=on}}\n|position       = {{rlp|LK|PR|SR}}\n|club1          = [[Brisbane Broncos]]\n|year1start     = 2010\n|year1end       = 13\n|appearances1   = 32\n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    = 0\n|points1        = 4\n|club2          = [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles|Manly Sea Eagles]]\n|year2start     = 2014\n|year2end       = 15\n|appearances2   = 38\n|tries2         = 1\n|goals2         = 0\n|fieldgoals2    = 0\n|points2        = 4\n|club3          = [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]]\n|year3start     = 2016\n|year3end       = \n|appearances3   = 10\n|tries3         = 0\n|goals3         = 0\n|fieldgoals3    = 0\n|points3        = 0\n|club4          = [[Canberra Raiders]]\n|year4start     = 2017\n|year4end       = present\n|appearances4   = 60\n|tries4         = 1\n|goals4         = 0\n|fieldgoals4    = 0\n|points4        = 4\n|teamA          = [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]]\n|yearAstart     = 2014\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 6\n|triesA         = 0\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    = 0\n|pointsA        = 0\n|retired        = \n|source         = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/players/dunamis-lui/summary.html|title=Dunamis Lui - Career Stats & Summary|publisher=Rugby League Project|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n|updated        = 7 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Dunamis Lui''' (born 16 February 1990) is a [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] international [[rugby league]] footballer who plays as a {{rlp|pr|sr}} and {{rlp|lk}} for the [[Canberra Raiders]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]]. \n\nHe previously played for the [[Brisbane Broncos]], [[Manly Warringah Sea Eagles]] and the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] in the [[National Rugby League|NRL]].\n\n==Background==\nLui was born in [[Brisbane|Brisbane, Queensland]], Australia. He is of [[Samoan people|Samoan descent]].\n\nLui played his junior football for the [[Aspley Broncos|Aspley Devils]] and [[Past Brothers|Brisbane Brothers]] before being signed by the [[Brisbane Broncos]]. \n[[File:dunamislui.jpg|thumb|right|Lui playing for the Broncos in 2009]]\nLui played for the Broncos [[National Youth Competition (rugby league)|NYC]] team from 2008 to 2010.<ref>[http://rleague.com/players/Dunamis-Lui_2094/Matches/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906192941/http://rleague.com/players/Dunamis-Lui_2094/Matches/|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> Lui has played for the Queensland Schoolboys team. Lui has played for the AIS team.\n\n==Playing career==\n===2010===\nIn round 5 of the [[2010 NRL season]], Lui made his [[National Rugby League|NRL]] debut for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] against the [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]] off the interchange bench in the Broncos 34-16 loss at [[WIN Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/broncos-name-dunamis-lui-in-nrl-squad-for-dragons-clash/story-e6frep5x-1225850485474|title=Broncos Name Dunamis Lui in NRL Squad for Dragons Clash|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/nrl/st-george-illawarra-dragons-v-brisbane-broncos-at-win-stadium/story-e6frep5x-1225851911501|title=Dragons v Broncos at Win Stadium|publisher=Couriermail.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In round 6 against the [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]], Lui scored his first NRL career try in the Broncos 44-16 win at [[Suncorp Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Wayne Heming|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/broncos-punish-gummy-sharks-20100418-smah.html|title=Broncos punish gummy Sharks|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2010-04-18|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished his debut year in the NRL with him playing in 4 matches and scoring a try for the [[Brisbane Broncos]].\n\n===2011===\nOn 12 May 2011, Lui re-signed with Brisbane on a two-year contract to the end of the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8248364|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130730075833/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8248364|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-07-30|title=Broncos sign two more young NRL hopefuls|publisher=Wwos.ninemsn.com.au|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished the [[2011 NRL season]] with him playing in 6 matches for the Broncos.\n\n===2012===\nLui finished the [[2012 NRL season]] with him played in 9 matches for Brisbane.\n\n===2013===\nOn 28 August 2013, Lui signed a one-year contract with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] starting in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/brisbane-prop-dunamis-lui-poised-to-leave-broncos-to-join-manly-sea-eagles-or-cronulla-sharks/story-fni3gv5x-1226705224909|title=Dunamis Lui Poised to Leave Broncos|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seaeagles.com.au/news-display/eagles/86013 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019011536/http://www.seaeagles.com.au/news-display/eagles/86013|date=19 October 2013}}</ref> Lui played in 13 matches in his last year for the [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[2013 NRL season]].\n\n===2014===\nIn round 1 of the [[2014 NRL season]], Lui made his club debut for the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]] off the interchange bench in the club's 23-22 loss at [[Brookvale Oval]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/nrl-premiership/anthony-watmough-has-declared-his-sides-performance-on-the-weekend-as-not-up-to-nrl-standard/story-e6frf3ru-1226851929219|title=Anthony Watmough Has Declared His Side's Performance as Not up to NRL Standard|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2014, Lui played for [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] in the [[Pacific Rugby League International#2014 test|2014 Pacific Rugby League International]] against [[Fiji national rugby league team|Fiji]] off the interchange bench in Samoa's 32-16 win at [[Penrith Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/gutsy-samoa-secures-place-in-four-nations-tournament-following-win-over-fiji/story-fni3fbgz-1226904268873|title=Gutsy Samoa Secures Place in Four Nations Tournament|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In round 17 against the [[Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]], Lui scored his first club try for Manly-Warringah in the 23-16 loss at [[ANZ Stadium]], Lui scoring his first try since round 6 of the [[2010 NRL season]] for the [[Brisbane Broncos]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Sonter|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/rugby-league-match-centre/live-bulldogs-v-sea-eagles-20140704-3bdjf.html|title=Live: Bulldogs v Sea Eagles|publisher=Smh.com.au|date=2014-07-04|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished off his first year with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] with him playing in 21 matches and scoring a try in the [[2014 NRL season]]. On 7 October 2014, Lui was selected in [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] 24-man squad for the [[2014 Rugby League Four Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/toa-samoa-name-four-nations-squad/tabid/10874/newsid/82434/default.aspx|title=Toa Samoa name Four Nations squad|publisher=NRL.com|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui played in 2 matches in the tournament.\n\n===2015===\nOn 23 January, Lui was named in Manly's [[2015 Auckland Nines]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/sea-eagles-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|title=SEA EAGLES UNVEIL 2015 NINES SQUAD|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2015-01-23|accessdate=2015-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716054235/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/sea-eagles-unveil-2015-nines-squad/|archive-date=16 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 2 May, Lui played for [[Samoa national rugby league team|Samoa]] in the 2015 [[Pacific Rugby League International#Polynesian Cup|Polynesian Cup]] battle against [[Tonga national rugby league team|Tonga]], playing off the interchange bench in Samoa's 18-16 win at [[Cbus Super Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/nrl/video-sam-kasiano-try-saving-tackle-on-jorge-taufua-secures-pacific-test-win-for-samoan-against-tonga/story-e6frf3ou-1227331678892|title=Video|publisher=Foxsports.com.au|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> On 16 September, Lui signed a two-year contract with [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] starting in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nrl.com/dragons-sign-dunamis-lui/tabid/10874/newsid/89857/default.aspx|title=Dragons sign Sea Eagles forward|publisher=NRL.com|date=2015-09-16|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zerotackle.com/nrl/dragons-sign-dunamis-lui-19036/|title=Dragons sign Dunamis Lui &#124; NRL|publisher=Zero Tackle|date=|accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Lui finished his last year with the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] with him playing in 17 matches in the [[2015 NRL season]].\n\n===2016===\nIn February, Lui played for [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] in the [[2016 NRL Auckland Nines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/dragons-name-2016-nines-squad/|title=Dragons name 2016 Nines squad|publisher=Rugby League Week|date=2016-01-29|accessdate=2016-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204025959/http://rugbyleagueweek.com.au/dragons-name-2016-nines-squad/|archive-date=4 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In round 1 of the [[2016 NRL season]], Lui made his club debut for [[St. George Illawarra Dragons|St. George Illawarra]] against the [[Melbourne Storm]], playing off the interchange bench in St. George's 18-16 loss at [[AAMI Park]].<ref>http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/teams/storm/melbourne-storm-defeat-the-dragons-1816-at-aami-park/news-story/3f45ed468af51012df6c60a6182d7d86</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2016, Lui signed a two-year deal with the [[Canberra Raiders]] commencing in 2017.\n\n===2018===\nLui signed a further three-year extension on August 8, 2018, keeping him at the [[Canberra Raiders]] until the end of the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/dunamis-lui-pens-canberra-raiders-extension-20180808-p4zw5s.html|title=Dunamis Lui pens Canberra Raiders extension|first=Caden|last=Helmers|date=8 August 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nLui made 27 appearances for Canberra in the [[2019 NRL season]] as the club reached their first grand final in 25 years.  Lui played from the bench in the [[2019 NRL Grand Final]] in which Canberra were defeated by the [[Sydney Roosters]] at [[ANZ Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-grand-final-player-ratings-roosters-and-raiders-hits-and-misses-20191006-p52y53.html/|title=NRL grand final player ratings: Roosters and Raiders hits and misses|website=SMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/49950757/|title=Sydney Roosters beat Canberra Raiders to win NRL Grand Final|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwos.nine.com.au/nrl/grand-final-ricky-stuart-reaction-canberra-raiders-six-again-jack-wighton/ae39b639-d375-4608-89a6-af6285c3d635/|title=How Ricky Stuart reacted to grand final 'six-again' refereeing shocker|website=WWOS}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.raiders.com.au/teams/telstra-premiership/canberra-raiders/dunamis-lui/ Canberra Raiders profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151224053358/http://www.dragons.com.au/team/profiles/dunamis_lui.html St. George Illawarra Dragons profile]\n\n{{Canberra Raiders squad}}\n{{Samoa 2014 Rugby League Four Nations squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lui, Dunamis}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Australian rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Samoan descent]]\n[[Category:Samoa national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Samoan rugby league players]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Manly Warringah Sea Eagles players]]\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Canberra Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Norths Devils players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league locks]]\n[[Category:Rugby league props]]\n[[Category:Rugby league second-rows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Brisbane]]\n", "name_user": "Bbatt42", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunamis_Lui"}
