{"title_page": "Transport for Wales Rail Services", "text_new": "{{about|the train operating company|the government-owned regulating body|Transport for Wales|the former train operator|Arriva Trains Wales}}\n{{short description|Train operating company in Wales, UK}}\n{{Use British English |date=September 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rail company\n|name           = {{ubl|Transport for Wales|{{small|{{lang|cy|Trafnidiaeth Cymru}}}}}}\n|logo           = Transport wales logo18.svg\n|logo_size      = 200px\n|image          = Hereford - Keolis Amey 175003 Carmarthen service.JPG\n|image_size     = 250px\n|image_filename = Hereford - Keolis Amey 175003 Carmarthen service.JPG\n|caption        = Transport for Wales unit [[British Rail Class 175|175003]] at {{stnlink|Hereford}}\n|nameforarea    = region\n|regions        = [[Wales]]\n|secregions     = {{ubl|[[North West England]]|[[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]]|[[Gloucestershire]]}}\n|fleet          =\n|franchise      = {{ubl|[[Wales & Borders franchise]]|14 October 2018 \u2013 15 October 2033}}\n|stations       =\n|stationsop     = 247<ref>{{Cite news|title=Transport for Wales unveil plan to invest in Welsh stations over 15 years|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/17904613.transport-wales-unveil-plan-invest-welsh-stations-15-years|last=Hoppe|first=Joe|date=16 September 2019|access-date=18 February 2020|work=[[South Wales Argus]]|publisher=[[Newsquest]]|location=Newport}}/</ref>\n|predecessor    = [[Arriva Trains Wales]]\n|parent_company = {{ubl|[[Keolis]]|[[Amey plc|Amey]]}}\n|website        = {{ubl|{{Official URL}} {{small|(English)}}|{{URL|trctrenau.cymru}} {{small|(Welsh)}}}}\n|gauge          = {{Track gauge|standard}}\n|abbr           = AW<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalrail.co.uk/tocs_maps/tocs/AW.aspx|title=Transport for Wales (AW)|date=6 February 2020|access-date=18 February 2020|website=National Rail Enquiries|department=Train Operating Companies|publisher=[[National Rail]]}}</ref>\n|map            =\n}}\n'''Transport for Wales Rail Services''' (TfW Rail Services) is a Welsh [[train operating company]] run by [[Keolis]]/[[Amey plc|Amey]] Wales Cymru Limited.<ref name=\"comphouse\">{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/11391059|title=Keolis Amey Wales Cymru Limited|website=[[gov.uk]]|publisher=[[Companies House]]|access-date=5 November 2018|quote=Company number: 11391059}}</ref> TfW Rail Services uses the brand names '''Transport for Wales''' and '''TfW Rail''' ({{lang-cy|'''Trafnidiaeth Cymru'''}}<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://trctrenau.cymru/|title=''Hafan''|access-date=18 February 2020|website=TrC Trenau|trans-website=TfW Rail|publisher=Transport for Wales Rail Services|language=cy|trans-title=Homeoage|quote={{lang|cy|Darganfod hyd a lled rhwydwaith Trafnidiaeth Cymru.}} [Find out the full extent of the Transport for Wales network].}}</ref> and {{lang|cy|'''TrC Trenau'''}})<ref>{{Cite tweet|author=Transport for Wales|number=1046761991698882561|user=transport_wales|title=Bydd yr ap TrC Trenau ar gael i\u2019w lawrlwytho maes o lawr ar iOS ac Android. Rydym ni\u2019n gwybod y byddwch angen amser i gael trefn arno, felly bydd yr ap presennol yn dal i weithio tan ddiwedd y flwyddyn. #dechrautaith|date=1 October 2018|access-date=18 February 2020|language=cy|trans-title=The TfW Rail app will be available for download on iOS and Android. We know you will need time to get it sorted, so the current app will continue to work until the end of the year. #StartingAJourney}}</ref> for day-to-day operations.\n\nTfW Rail Services was awarded the contract for the [[Wales & Borders franchise|Wales and Borders franchise]] by the (commercially separate) government body [[Transport for Wales]] in 2018. TfW Rail Services commenced rail operations on 14 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-45786582|title=New \u00a35bn Wales rail franchise starts|date=14 October 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|access-date=30 January 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Wales & Borders pass nos.png|thumb|right|320px|Passenger journeys on the Wales & Borders franchise from 2010-11 to 2018\u201319.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dataportal.orr.gov.uk/statistics/usage/passenger-rail-usage/passenger-journeys-by-train-operating-company-table-1212/|title=Passenger journeys by train operating company - Table 12.12 &#124; ORR Data Portal|website=dataportal.orr.gov.uk}}</ref>]]\n\nIn October 2016 four bids were shortlisted for the next [[Wales & Borders franchise]]: [[Abellio (transport company)|Abellio]], the incumbent operator [[Arriva Trains Wales|Arriva]], a [[Keolis]]/[[Amey plc|Amey]] joint venture, and [[MTR Corporation]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://gov.wales/newsroom/transport/2016/161013-rail-operator-shortlist-revealed/?lang=en |title=Rail operator shortlist revealed |date=12 October 2016 |access-date=30 September 2018  |publisher=[[Welsh Government]] |quote=Four bidders have been selected to progress to the next stage in the procurement process to operate rail services in Wales and the Borders from October 2018 as well take forward key aspects of the next stage of Metro.}}</ref><ref name=RGI131016>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/policy/single-view/view/wales-borders-bidders-asked-to-submit-metro-options.html |title=Wales & Borders bidders asked to propose Metro options |magazine=[[Railway Gazette International]] |publisher=[[DVV Media Group]] |location=[[Sutton, Greater London|Sutton]] |issn=0373-5346 |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=30 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Arriva withdrew from the bidding process, followed in February 2018 by Abellio, after the collapse of its partner [[Carillion]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/main-line/arriva-pulls-out-of-wales-borders-franchise-contest.html?channel=524 |title=Arriva pulls out of Wales & Borders franchise contest |magazine=[[International Railway Journal]] |publisher=[[Simmons-Boardman Publishing]] |location=Falmouth |issn=0744-5326 |date=30 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-41809874 |title=Arriva Trains Wales drops out of Welsh rail franchise bid |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=30 October 2017 |access-date=30 September 2018 | quote=The firm that runs most of Wales' rail network has pulled out of the contest to continue running it from 2018. Arriva has said Arriva Trains Wales was \"no longer participating in the Wales and Borders competition\", adding it had \"not been an easy decision\".}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-43169116 |title=Abellio ends rail bid after Carillion collapse |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=23 February 2018 |access-date=30 September 2018  |quote=One of the three remaining bidders for the next Wales and Borders rail franchise has pulled out. Abellio Rail Cymru (ARC) said it had been unable to overcome the collapse of its partner construction company, Carillion. Its exit from the process leaves just MTR and Keolis Amey bidding to run the franchise, which will operate the South Wales Metro.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/passenger/single-view/view/abellio-pulls-out-of-wales-borders-bidding.html |title=Abellio pulls out of Wales & Borders bidding |magazine=[[International Railway Journal]] |date=23 February 2018  |publisher=[[Simmons-Boardman Publishing]] |location=Falmouth |issn=0744-5326}}</ref> In May 2018, the franchise was awarded to Keolis Amey Wales Cymru. It commenced on 14 October 2018 and runs for 15 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-44221184 |title=Wales' rail and metro franchise to be run by Keolis Amey |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=23 May 2018 |access-date=30 September 2018  |quote=A \u00a35bn contract to run Wales' rail service for the next 15 years has been awarded to two European firms, who will run it jointly. France's Keolis and Spanish-owned Amey's bid triumphed over a rival offer from Hong Kong's MTR commuter railways. It will also drive forward the south Wales Metro in Cardiff and the valleys.}}</ref>\n\nUnlike the previous franchise, which was awarded by the [[Department for Transport]], the new franchise was awarded by [[Transport for Wales]], on behalf of the [[Welsh Government]].<ref name=RGI131016/>\n\nAs of January 2020 Keolis Amey has been fined \u00a32.3 million by the Welsh government for poor performance of rail services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/trains-transport-wales-keolis-amey-17539543|title=Train operator Keolis Amey fined \u00a32.3m for poor performance|date=9 January 2020|website=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]}}</ref> The company is also expected to be criticised by the [[Welsh Language Commissioner]] later in 2020 for reportedly breaking legislation on Welsh language provision six times since taking over the franchise in 2018.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-51011565|title=Transport for Wales 'breaks Welsh language rules'|date=7 January 2020|access-date=12 January 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> TfW Rail told the BBC that it did not believe any rules had been broken.<ref name=\":2\" /> Complaints included that Welsh was given lesser treatment on self-service machines, websites, and on the mobile app, that correspondence was not issued fully in Welsh, that train tickets were printed only in English, and that station and train announcements were not always made bilingually.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Services==\n\nTypical TfW weekday off-peak service is as follows:<ref>[https://tfwrail.wales/travel-updates/train-times Train Times]. Transport for Wales Rail.</ref>\n<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#{{National Rail colour|Transport for Wales Rail}}; color:White\" | North Wales Coast Line\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| {{rws|Cardiff Central}} to {{rws|Holyhead}} || 8tpd ||{{rws|Newport}}, {{rws|Cwmbran}}, {{rws|Pontypool & New Inn}}, {{rws|Abergavenny}}, {{rws|Hereford}}, {{rws|Leominster}} (3tpd), {{rws|Ludlow}} (7tpd), {{rws|Craven Arms}} (7tpd), {{rws|Church Stretton}} (7tpd), {{rws|Shrewsbury}}, {{rws|Gobowen}} (7tpd), {{rws|Chirk}} (7tpd), {{rws|Ruabon}} (7tpd), {{rws|Wrexham General}}, {{rws|Chester}}, [[Shotton railway station|Shotton]] (4tpd), {{rws|Flint}}, {{rws|Prestatyn}} (7tpd), {{rws|Rhyl}}, [[Abergele & Pensarn railway station|Abergele & Pensarn]] (3tpd), [[Colwyn Bay railway station|Colwyn Bay]], {{rws|Llandudno Junction}}, [[Conwy railway station|Conwy]] (3tpd), [[Penmaenmawr railway station|Penmaenmawr]] (3tpd), [[Llanfairfechan railway station|Llanfairfechan]] (3tpd) {{rws|Bangor|Wales}} (7tpd), {{rws|Llanfairpwll}} (7tpd), {{rws|Bodorgan}} (5tpd), {{rws|Ty Croes}} (5tpd), {{rws|Rhosneigr}} (5tpd) and {{rws|Valley}} (5tpd)<br /><small>0534 from [[Holyhead railway station|Holyhead]] and 1716 from [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] is ''[[Premier Service]]'' which calls at fewer stops and has 1st class accommodation available with meals included.<br>Only 7 tpd terminate in Holyhead as one turns off at [[Llandudno Junction railway station|Llandudno Junction]] and terminates at [[Llandudno railway station|Llandudno]], calling at [[Deganwy railway station|Deganwy]] en route.</small>\n| {{brc|175|n}}\n|-\n|Cardiff Central to Holyhead (''Premier Service'')\n|1tpd\n|Newport, Cwmbran <small>(Holyhead-bound only)</small>, Pontypool <small>(Holyhead-bound only)</small>, Abergavenny <small>(Holyhead-bound only)</small>, Hereford, Ludlow <small>(Cardiff-bound only)</small>, Shrewsbury, Wrexham General, Chester, Flint, Rhyl, Colwyn Bay, Llandudno Junction and Bangor\n|[[British Rail Class 67|67]]\n|-\n| {{rws|Birmingham International}} to Holyhead || {{abbr|0.5|1 train every 2