ck}}, Clarbeston Road, Whitland and Llanelli\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#{{National Rail colour|Transport for Wales Rail}}; color:White\" | Swanline\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| Swansea to Cardiff Central || {{abbr|0.5|1 train every 2 hours}} || {{rws|Llansamlet}}, {{rws|Skewen}}, Neath, {{rws|Briton Ferry}}, {{rws|Baglan}}, Port Talbot Parkway, {{rws|Pyle}}, Bridgend, Pencoed and Pontyclun|| {{brc|150|n}}, {{brc|153|n}}, {{brc|158|n}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#B06040; color:White\" | West Wales-Gloucestershire Line\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| {{rws|Maesteg}} to {{rws|Cheltenham Spa}} || 1 (Alternates with the Fishguard Harbour to Gloucester Service) ||{{rws|Maesteg (Ewenny Road)}}, {{rws|Garth|Bridgend}}, {{rws|Tondu}}, {{rws|Sarn}}, {{rws|Wildmill}}, [[Bridgend]], {{rws|Pencoed}}, {{rws|Llanharan}}, {{rws|Pontyclun}}, [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]], [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], {{rws|Severn Tunnel Junction}}, {{rws|Caldicot}}, {{rws|Chepstow}}, {{rws|Lydney}} and {{rws|Gloucester}} <br /><small>Some trains terminate at Cardiff Central, rather than Cheltenham Spa</small>||{{brc|150|n}}, {{brc|153|n}}, {{brc|158|n}}, {{brc|170|n}}, {{brc|175|n}}\n|-\n|[[Fishguard Harbour railway station|Fishguard Harbour]] to [[Gloucester railway station|Gloucester]]\n|4tpd\n|[[Fishguard and Goodwick]], [[Clarbeston Road]], [[Clunderwen railway station|Clunderwen]], [[Whitland]], [[Carmarthen]], [[Ferryside]], [[Kidwelly]], [[Pembrey and Burry Port railway station|Pembrey and Burry Port]], [[Llanelli]], [[Gowerton]], [[Swansea railway station]], [[Neath]], [[Port Talbot Parkway railway station|Port Talbot Parkway]], [[Bridgend]], [[Pencoed]], [[Llanharan]], [[Pontyclun]], [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]], [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Severn Tunnel Junction railway station|Severn Tunnel Junction]], [[Caldicot, Monmouthshire|Caldicot]], [[Chepstow]] and [[Lydney]]\n<small>Some trains terminate at Cardiff Central, rather than Gloucester</small>\n|[[British Rail Class 150|150]], [[British Rail Class 158|158]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#303080; color:White\" | Ebbw Valley Railway\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| Bridgend/Cardiff Central to {{rws|Ebbw Vale Town}} || 1 || Pencoed, Pontyclun, Cardiff Central, {{rws|Pye Corner}}, {{rws|Rogerstone}}, {{rws|Risca & Pontymister}}, {{rws|Cross Keys}}, {{rws|Newbridge|Wales}}, {{rws|Llanhilleth}} and {{rws|Ebbw Vale Parkway}} ||{{brc|150|n}}, {{brc|153|n}}, {{brc|158|n}}, {{brc|170|n}}, {{brc|175|n}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#50B030; color:White\" | Rhymney Line\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| {{rws|Penarth}}/Cardiff Central to {{rws|Bargoed}}/{{rws|Rhymney}} || 4 || {{rws|Dingle Road}}, {{rws|Grangetown}}, Cardiff Central, {{rws|Cardiff Queen Street}}, {{rws|Heath High Level}}, {{rws|Llanishen}}, {{rws|Lisvane & Thornhill}}, {{rws|Caerphilly}}, {{rws|Aber}}, {{rws|Energlyn & Churchill Park}} (2tph), {{rws|Llanbradach}}, {{rws|Ystrad Mynach}}, {{rws|Hengoed}}, {{rws|Pengam}}, {{rws|Gilfach Fargoed}} (1tph), {{rws|Bargoed}}, {{rws|Brithdir}} (1tph), {{rws|Tir-Phil}} (1tph) and {{rws|Pontlottyn}} (1tph) || {{brc|142|n}}, {{brc|143|n}}, {{brc|150|n}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#E00810; color:White\" | Merthyr & Vale of Glamorgan Lines\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| Bridgend to {{rws|Aberdare}} || 1 || {{rws|Llantwit Major}}, {{rws|Rhoose Cardiff International Airport}}, {{rws|Barry}}, {{rws|Barry Docks}}, {{rws|Cadoxton}}, {{rws|Dinas Powys}}, {{rws|Eastbrook}}, {{rws|Cogan}}, Grangetown, Cardiff Central, Cardiff Queen Street, {{rws|Cathays}}, {{rws|Llandaf}}, {{rws|Radyr}}, {{rws|Taffs Well}}, {{rws|Trefforest}}, {{rws|Pontypridd}}, {{rws|Abercynon}}, {{rws|Penrhiwceiber}}, {{rws|Mountain Ash}}, {{rws|Fernhill}} and {{rws|Cwmbach}} ||  rowspan=\"3\" |{{brc|142|n}}, {{brc|143|n}}, {{brc|150|n}}\n|-\n| {{rws|Barry Island}} to Aberdare || 1 || Barry, Barry Docks, Cadoxton, Dinas Powys, Eastbrook, Cogan, Grangetown, Cardiff Central, Cardiff Queen Street, Cathays, Llandaf, Radyr, Taffs Well, Trefforest, Pontypridd, Abercynon, Penrhiwceiber, Mountain Ash, Fernhill and Cwmbach\n|-\n| Barry Island to {{rws|Merthyr Tydfil}} || 2 || Barry, Barry Docks, Cadoxton, Dinas Powys, Eastbrook, Cogan, Grangetown, Cardiff Central, Cardiff Queen Street, Cathays, Llandaf, Radyr, Taffs Well, {{rws|Trefforest Estate}}, Trefforest, Pontypridd, Abercynon, {{rws|Quakers Yard}}, {{rws|Merthyr Vale}}, {{rws|Troed-y-rhiw}} and {{rws|Pentre-bach}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#9060A0; color:White\" | Rhondda Line\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| Cardiff Central to {{rws|Treherbert}} || 2 || Cardiff Queen Street, Cathays, Llandaf, Radyr, Taffs Well, Trefforest, Pontypridd, {{rws|Trehafod}}, {{rws|Porth}}, {{rws|Dinas Rhondda}}, {{rws|Tonypandy}}, {{rws|Llwynypia}}, {{rws|Ystrad Rhondda}}, {{rws|Ton Pentre}}, {{rws|Treorchy}} and {{rws|Ynyswen}} ||{{brc|142|n}}, {{brc|143|n}}, {{brc|150|n}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#E0B000; color:White\" | City & Coryton Lines\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| Radyr to {{rws|Coryton}} || 2 || {{rws|Danescourt}}, {{rws|Fairwater}}, {{rws|Waun-gron Park}}, {{rws|Ninian Park}}, Cardiff Central, Cardiff Queen Street, {{rws|Heath Low Level}}, {{rws|Ty Glas}}, {{rws|Birchgrove}}, {{rws|Rhiwbina}} and {{rws|Whitchurch|Wales}} ||{{brc|142|n}}, {{brc|143|n}},  {{brc|153|n}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#80C0E0; color:White\" | Butetown Branch Line\n|-\n! Route !! {{abbr|tph|trains per hour}} !! Calling at !! Class\n|-\n| {{rws|Cardiff Bay}} to Cardiff Queen Street || 5 ||''shuttle''||{{brc|142|n}}, {{brc|143|n}}, {{brc|150|n}}, {{brc|153|n}}\n|}\n\n==Planned improvements==\n{{Speculation section|date=February 2020|wibble}}\n<!-- Remember, these plans are not set in stone. We shouldn't speculate on what might happen, so all future plans should be reliably sourced -->\nThere are plans to improve services between 2018 and 2033 as part of the new franchise:<ref name=WhatSW>{{cite web|url=http://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-south-west-and-mid-wales |title=What this means for Mid and South West Wales |website=tfw.gov.wales |publisher=[[Transport for Wales]] |access-date=30 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=WhatSE>{{cite web |url=http://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-south-east-wales |title=What's Happening In South East Wales|website=tfw.gov.wales |publisher=[[Transport for Wales]]|access-date=30 September 2018 |quote=overhead electric, battery and diesel}}</ref>\n\n'''North Wales and North West England'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-north-wales|title=What's Happening in North Wales |website=tfw.gov.wales|publisher=[[Transport for Wales]]]|access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n* A new hourly {{stnlnk|Liverpool Lime Street}} to Chester service was introduced in May 2019, with limited services extended to [[Wrexham General railway station|Wrexham General]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deeside.com/transport-for-wales-rebrand-gets-underway-on-the-wrexham-to-bidston-line/|title=Transport for Wales rebrand gets underway on the Wrexham to Bidston line|website=deeside.com|access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n* [[British Rail Class 230|Class 230 ''D-Trains'']] are scheduled for introduction on services on the [[Borderlands line|Borderlands]], [[Conwy Valley line|Conwy Valley]] and Crewe-Chester lines during 2019. The operator had indicated an introduction date of Summer 2019, but this has been pushed back awaiting delivery of the stock from manufacturer [[Vivarail]].\n* Twelve refurbished [[British Rail Mark 4|Mark 4]] carriages for the {{stnlnk|Holyhead}} to {{stnlnk|Cardiff Central}} ''[[Premier Service]]'' by the end of 2019, to replace the [[British Rail Mark 3|Mark 3]] carriages. The first Mark 4 sets were released by LNER in July 2019 following the introduction of Azuma services and were released to Transport for Wales by 2020.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1149990285369389056|user=That_Train_Guy|title=Another One Bites the Dust!  Ex- @LNER  Mark IV coaching stock 'BN29' passing Biggleswade with 66735 'Peterborough United' providing the power as 5Z91 0858 Bounds Green T&R.S.M.D to Worksop Down Yard. The train was running 42 minutes late.|date=13 July 2019|author=Graeme|access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n* Increase {{stnlnk|Wrexham Central}} to {{stnlnk|Bidston}} services to 2tph by December 2021, as part of the [[North Wales Metro]].\n* Introduction of a new hourly Liverpool to {{stnlnk|Llandudno}} and {{stnlnk|Shrewsbury}} service, and a new two-hourly Liverpool to {{stnlnk|Cardiff Central}} service from December 2022.\n* Introduction of a direct {{stnlnk|Manchester Airport}} to {{stnlnk|Bangor|Wales}} service from December 2022.\n* Introduce the new fleet of [[CAF Civity|Civity]] diesel multiple units (DMUs) to the [[North Wales Coast line]] and other North Wales routes during 2022.\n* Invest in {{stnlnk|Shotton}} and {{stnlnk|Wrexham General}} stations from April 2024, and in {{stnlnk|Chester}} station by 2028.\n* Invest to co-fund new station buildings at {{stnlnk|Blaenau Ffestiniog}}.\n* Introduce new [[Community rail|Community Rail Partnerships]] on the [[North Wales Coast Line]] and the [[Welsh Marches line|Crewe to Hereford line]].\n\n'''South West and Mid Wales and the Borders'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-south-west-and-mid-wales|title=What's Happening in South West and Mid Wales |website=tfw.gov.wales|publisher=[[Transport for Wales]]|access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/whats-happening-wales-borders|title=What's Happening in the Borders|website=tfw.gov.wales|publisher=[[Transport for Wales]]|access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n* Refurbished [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170 ''Turbostar'']] two-car DMUs on services to West Wales, Ebbw Vale and Maesteg from 2019, and the [[Heart of Wales line]] from 2022, to replace [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153 ''Super Sprinters'']].\n* Open a [[Bow Street railway station|new station at Bow Street]] in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-40753111|title=\u00a34m promised for new railway station|date=28 July 2017|work=BBC News|access-date=23 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* An additional service every day on the [[Heart of Wales line]] from December 2022.\n* A consistent 1&nbsp;tph on the [[Cambrian Line|Cambrian line]] from Shrewsbury to {{stnlnk|Aberystwyth}} from December 2022.\n* New [[CAF Civity|Civity]] DMUs on the [[Cambrian line]] during 2022, to replace the [[British Rail Class 158|Class 158 ''Express Sprinters'']].\n* Introduce new two and three-car new diesel multiple units for the {{stnlnk|Milford Haven}} to {{stnlnk|Manchester Piccadilly}} service by 2023, to replace the [[British Rail Class 175|Class 175 ''Coradias'']].\n* A first-class service between {{stnlnk|Swansea}} and Manchester from December 2024.\n* Additional summer Sunday services from May 2023 between {{stnlnk|Tywyn}} and {{stnlnk|Pwllheli}} \u2013 including a new 1 tph express service between major centres by 2025.\n* Invest in {{stnlnk|Carmarthen}} and {{stnlnk|Machynlleth}} stations in 2021, and {{stnlnk|Llanelli}} station in 2025.\n* Introduce a new [[Community rail|Community Rail Partnership]] for the [[West Wales line]].\n\n'''South East Wales'''<ref name=\"WhatSE\" />\n* Ticket machines were introduced at all [[South Wales Metro]] stations in 2019.\n* [[British Rail Class 769|Class 769 ''Flex'']] bi-mode multiple units (BMMUs) were delivered to Cardiff Canton Depot in Summer 2019,<ref>{{Citation|last=Llemiles|title=English: Former Class 319 Cheriton (unit 319008), destined to be a British Rail Class 769 at Cardiff Canton Depot. Awaiting final modifications before entering service with Transport for Wales Rail Services.|date=8 August 2019|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:British_Rail_Class_769.jpg|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> and are scheduled to run on the [[Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes|Valley Lines]] by the end of 2019.\n* Replace all [[British Rail Class 142|Class 142]] and [[British Rail Class 143|143 ''Pacers'']] by December 2019.\n* 4tph between [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] and [[Bridgend railway station|Bridgend]] (direct, Monday to Saturday) from December 2019.\n* Introduce pay-as-you-go for users of [[Contactless smartcards on the railways of Great Britain|smart cards]] by April 2020.\n* Increasing capacity of trains on early morning services to Cardiff Central from 2-car services to 4-car services.\n* A new 1 train per hour (tph) {{stnlnk|Ebbw Vale Town}} to {{stnlnk|Newport}} service from May 2021.\n* 4tph between {{stnlnk|Treherbert}}, [[Merthyr Tydfil railway station|Merthyr Tydfil]], [[Aberdare railway station|Aberdare]] and Cardiff from December 2022, operated by [[Stadler Citylink|''Citylink'' tram-trains]].\n* 6tph between [[Cardiff Queen Street railway station|Cardiff Queen Street]] and {{stnlnk|Cardiff Bay}} from December 2022.\n* Hourly {{stnlnk|Cheltenham Spa}} to [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] services from December 2022.\n* Introduce new [[Stadler FLIRT|FLIRT]] diesel-electric multiple units (DEMUs) on the [[Ebbw Valley Railway|Ebbw Vale]] and [[Maesteg Line|Maesteg]] lines during 2022.\n* Introduce new [[Stadler FLIRT|FLIRT]] tri-mode multiple units (TMMUs) between {{stnlnk|Penarth}}, {{stnlnk|Barry}} and {{stnlnk|Bridgend}} to [[Rhymney railway station|Rhymney]] and [[Coryton railway station|Coryton]] during 2023.\n* 2tph between Cardiff and Bridgend via the [[Vale of Glamorgan Line]] from December 2023.\n* 4tph throughout on the [[Rhymney line]] from December 2023.\n* Introduce [[Stadler Citylink|''Citylink'' tram-trains]] to the [[Cardiff City Line|City Line]] during 2023.\n* Eliminate diesel use on the Central Metro lines (north of {{stnlnk|Cardiff Queen Street}}) by 2024.\n* Open new stations at [[Cardiff Parkway railway station|Cardiff Parkway]] in February 2020, {{stnlnk|Crwys Road}}, {{stnlnk|Loudoun Square}} and {{stnlnk|Cardiff Bay (The Flourish)||Cardiff Bay}} by December 2023, [[Treforest Estate railway station|Treforest Estate]] by December 2025, and {{stnlnk|Gabalfa}} by 2028.\n* Invest in [[Merthyr Tydfil railway station|Merthyr Tydfil]] from April 2020, [[Abergavenny railway station|Abergavenny]] from April 2023, and [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] and [[Chepstow railway station|Chepstow]] from April 2025.\n* Develop a fleet maintenance depot at [[Taff's Well|Taffs Well]] and a dedicated Infrastructure Management depot in the Valleys.\n* Build a Major Events Stabling Line (MESL) and a [[Llanwern railway station|new station]] in [[Llanwern]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfw.gov.wales/projects/south-wales-metro|title=South Wales Metro|website=tfw.gov.wales|publisher=[[Transport for Wales]]|access-date=23 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Current fleet==\n[[File:Caerdydd Canolog - Keolis Amey 143606 tr\u00ean i Abertawe.JPG|thumb|{{brc|143}} at {{stnlnk|Cardiff Central}} with \"These trains will terminate soon\" branding in 2019]]\nTfW Rail inherited a fleet of [[British Rail Class 142|Class 142]], [[British Rail Class 143|143]], [[British Rail Class 150|150]], [[British Rail Class 153|153]], [[British Rail Class 158|158]] and [[British Rail Class 175|175]] [[diesel multiple unit]]s and [[British Rail Mark 3|Mark 3]] carriages from Arriva Trains Wales, which had been refurbished starting from 2011 and had been fitted with WiFi in 2017. It has since acquired some [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170]] units (from September 2019 to February 2020) and more Class 153 units (in April 2019 and December 2019 to January 2020) from some English operators to work alongside and with the ex-ATW fleet, to add capacity and support new services.\n\n====Class 153 ''Super Sprinters''====\n\nIn April 2019 TfW Rail added 5 153s acquired from [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]] to the 8 it previously had. Four of these entered service the following month, and the fifth returned from works on 5 October 2019 as the first 153 on the whole GB rail network with PRM (Persons with Reduced Mobility) modifications, and entered service on 21 October 2019.\n\nIn October 2019, [[Porterbrook|Porterbrook Leasing Company]] announced that they will lease a further 9 Class 153 units to TfW for use on a short term basis.<ref name=\"news.tfwrail.wales\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.tfwrail.wales/news/extra-capacity-and-improved-trains-for-rail-passengers-in-wales|title=Extra capacity and improved trains for rail passengers across Wales and the borders|website=Transport For Wales News|language=en-GB|access-date=3 October 2019}}</ref> These comprise 5 153s from [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] which were delivered in December 2019 and started to enter service in January 2020, and 4 153s from [[East Midlands Railway]] which were delivered in January 2020 and started to enter service in February 2020.\n\n====Class 170 ''Turbostars''====\nIn September 2019 Transport for Wales took delivery of the first 3 of 12 total [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170 ''Turbostar'']] DMUs from [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]], with 3 more of the units following in November 2019, a further 4 in December 2019 and the last two in January and February 2020 respectively.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.tfwrail.wales/news/extra-trains-arrive-for-transport-for-wales|title=Extra trains arrive for Transport for Wales|website=Transport For Wales News|language=en-GB|access-date=5 September 2019}}</ref> Driver training had taken place from September 2019, and in April 2020, the last unit to enter service (3-car 170206) finally did so.\n\nOn 12 December 2019, 3-car 170202 worked TfW Rail's first Class 170 passenger services (between Bridgend and Ebbw Vale Town via Cardiff Central), and five units (three 3-car and two 2-car) were in passenger service on 16 December 2019. The units had been refurbished under Greater Anglia and are initially being used by TfW Rail cosmetically unchanged (other than the different operator logos), but as they will be retained for the duration of the franchise, it is planned that they will later receive further refurbishment to TfW Rail specification.\n\n====Class 142/143 ''Pacers'' and Mark 3 sets====\n\nAs of April 2019, all of TfW Rail's [[British Rail Class 142|Class 142]] & [[British Rail Class 143|143]] 'Pacer' railbus DMUs, which were intended to be withdrawn and replaced by 1 January 2020 PRM deadline but will now continue in service until July 2020 under dispensation from law,<ref name=\"news.tfwrail.wales\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilkinson |first1=Peter |title=The Railways (Interoperability) Regulations 2011 \u2013 Transport for Wales Rail Services Class 142s - 2020 accessibility deadline |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/855421/tfw-class-142s-2020-dispensation-letter.pdf |website=DfT |accessdate=1 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101125125/https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/855421/tfw-class-142s-2020-dispensation-letter.pdf |archivedate=1 January 2020 |date=4 December 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\nhave had advertising vinyls applied, with the messages 'The start of a new journey', 'The journey is almost over for old trains', and 'These trains will terminate soon', stating rolling stock, infrastructure and service improvements. The Mark 3 carriages for the locomotive-hauled trains have had Transport for Wales logos applied to the ex-Arriva Trains Wales livery, as they will be withdrawn and replaced in 2020.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Class 150, 153, 158 and 175 DMUs====\n\nThe rest of TfW Rail's rolling stock (the Class 150, 153, 158 and 175 DMUs), which will be withdrawn and replaced by 2023 (except the 9 \"shorter-term\" 153s which will be withdrawn by the end of 2020), is in the process of undergoing several changes. These include the application of Transport for Wales livery, and TfW Rail specification interior refurbishment (including new seat moquette, floor coverings and table surfaces, as well as [[Alternating current|AC]] and USB power sockets).{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn addition, the 150s/153s/158s staying until 2022-23 are receiving PRM-TSI 2020 (Persons with Reduced Mobility - Technical Specifications for Interoperability) modifications (the 175s exceed the [[Rail Vehicle Accessibility Regulations|RVAR]] 1998 they were built to and are accepted without modification).\n\n===Fleet summary===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Trainset\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Class\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Image\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Type\n!colspan=\"2\"|Top Speed\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Carriages\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Number\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Routes Operated\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Built\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n!mph\n!km/h\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" |Locomotive hauled stock\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Premier Service|''Premier Service'']]\n|[[British Rail Class 67|67]]\n|[[File:Alstom General Motors Class 67 No 67003 (7786994576).jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=\"center\"|[[Diesel locomotive|Loco]]\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |110\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |177\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\" |\u2013\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|rowspan=3|\n* {{small|Holyhead\u2013Cardiff Central}}\n* {{small|Holyhead (Llandudno)\u2013Manchester Piccadilly}}\n|align=center|1999\u20132000\n|-\n|[[British Rail Mark 3|Mark 3]]\n|[[File:Keolis Amey Mark 3 TSO 12185 at Crewe Carriage Shed (Arriva livery).JPG|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=\"center\"|[[Passenger car (rail)|Coach]]\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|align=\"center\"|1975\u201388\n|-\n|[[Driving Van Trailer]]\n|[[File:Arriva Trains Wales DVT at Cardiff Central by Jeremy Segrott.jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Control car]]\n| align=\"center\" |3\n| align=\"center\" |1988\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" |Diesel multiple units\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Pacer (train)|Pacer]]\n|[[British Rail Class 142|142]]\n|[[File:Caerdydd Canolog - Keolis Amey 142076.JPG|120x120px|alt=]]\n| rowspan=\"13\" align=\"center\" |[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n| align=\"center\" |75\n| align=\"center\" |121\n| align=\"center\" |2\n| align=\"center\" |15\n|\n* {{small|Valley Lines & Cardiff local routes}} <small>(plus 3 spare parts units)</small>\n| align=\"center\" |1985\u201387\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[British Rail Class 143|143]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[File:Radur - Keolis Amey 143624 tr\u00ean i Caerdydd Canolog.JPG|120x120px]]\n|align=\"center\"|75\n|align=\"center\"|121\n|align=\"center\"|2\n| align=\"center\" |15\n|\n* {{small|Valley Lines & Cardiff local routes}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |1985\u201386\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:ATW 2017 143.png|258x258px]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |[[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]]\n|[[British Rail Class 150|150/2]]\n|[[File:Stockport - Keolis-Amey 150284 (Arriva colours).JPG|120x120px]]\n|align=\"center\"|75\n|align=\"center\"|121\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|align=\"center\"|36\n|\n* {{small|Valley Lines & Cardiff local routes}}\n* {{small|Heart of Wales/West Wales lines}}\n* {{small|Regional services between South and West Wales, North West and South West England}}\n|align=\"center\"|1986\u201387\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[British Rail Class 153|153 ''Super Sprinter'']]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[File:Class 153 at Ty Glas station crop (geograph 6162860).jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=\"center\"|75\n|align=\"center\"|121\n| align=\"center\" |1\n| align=\"center\" |22\n|\n* {{small|Valley Lines & Cardiff local routes}}\n* {{small|Heart of Wales/West Wales lines}}\n* {{small|Crewe-Shrewsbury local services}}\n* {{small|Regional services between South and West Wales, North West and South West England}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |1987\u201388\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:Class 153 Transport for Wales Diagram.png|218x218px]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[British Rail Class 158|158/0 ''Express Sprinter'']]\n|rowspan=2|[[File:Crewe - Keolis-Amey 158830 Chester service.JPG|120x120px|alt=]]\n| align=\"center\" |90\n| align=\"center\" |140\n| align=\"center\" |2\n| align=\"center\" |24\n|\n* {{small|Cambrian line}}\n* {{small|Regional services between South and North Wales, North West and South West England}}\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|1990\u201391\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:Class 158 in the Transport for Wales livery.png|320px|alt=|left]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]/[[ADtranz]] [[Bombardier Turbostar|Turbostar]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[British Rail Class 170|170/2]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[File:TfW Rail 170208 at Cardiff Central 16 December 2019.jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|100\n|align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|161\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n* {{small|Maesteg Line}}\n* {{small|Ebbw Valley Railway}}\n* {{small|South Wales Main Line<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tfwrail.wales/one-year|title=One Year In|website=tfwrail.wales|language=en|access-date=5 November 2019}}</ref>}}\n| align=\"center\" |2002\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|8\n| align=\"center\" |1999\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |[[File:TfW Class 170-2 2 Car.png|alt=|341x341px]]\n[[File:TfW Class 170-2 3 Car.png|alt=|502x502px]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Alstom Coradia]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[British Rail Class 175|175/0 & 175/1]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[File:Hereford - Keolis Amey 175003 Carmarthen service.JPG|120x120px|alt=]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |100\n| rowspan=\"2\" |161\n| align=\"center\" |2\n| align=\"center\" |11\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{small|Regional services between North West England, North and South Wales}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" |1999\u20132001\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Train maintenance depots ===\nTfW Rail's current fleet is stored and maintained at the following depots.\n* [[Cardiff Canton TMD|Cardiff Canton]]: {{brc|142}}, {{brc|143}}, {{brc|150}}, {{brc|153}}, {{brc|170}} and {{brc|769}} units, and [[British Rail Class 67|locomotive-hauled]] [[British Rail Mark 3|trains]]. Also a stabling point for 158s and 175s.\n* [[Chester TMD|Chester]] ([[Alstom]]): {{brc|175}} units (main)\n* Machynlleth: {{brc|158}} units (main)\n* [[Holyhead TMD|Holyhead]]: Stabling point (refuelling and light maintenance) for locomotive-hauled trains and DMUs\n* [[Crewe Carriage Sidings]] ([[Arriva TrainCare]]): [[British Rail Class 150|Class 150]], [[British Rail Class 153|Class 153]] and [[British Rail Class 158|Class 158]] units, and [[British Rail Class 67|locomotive-hauled]] [[British Rail Mark 3|trains]]. Stabling point and light maintenance.\n\nDue to space limitations, Chrysalis Rail currently allows TfW Rail to store any unallocated units or carriages at its [[Landore TMD]] in Swansea, even if they are not being worked on. This arrangement has been in place since late 2019.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Past fleet==\n\nTrain types formerly operated by Transport for Wales Rail Services include:\n\n====Class 37-hauled Mark 2 sets====\n\nFrom June 2019 to March 2020, TfW Rail hired two Class 37-hauled Mark 2 sets to temporarily operate rush-hour services between Cardiff and Rhymney to add capacity. From January 2020 they were operating under PRM non-compliance dispensation, but were withdrawn in March due to decreasing reliability and replaced with trains formed of multiple Class 153 railcars coupled together, with many more of those now in the fleet.<ref name=\"news.tfwrail.wales\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Trainset\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Class\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Image\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Type\n!colspan=\"2\"|Top Speed\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Carriages\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Number\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Routes Operated\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Built\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n!mph\n!km/h\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" |Locomotive hauled stock\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n|[[British Rail Class 37|37]]\n|[[File:Class 37 at Llanishen (geograph 6162857).jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=center|[[Diesel locomotive|Loco]]\n|align=center|80\n|align=center|129\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|N/A\n|align=center|3\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Rhymney Line]]\n|align=center|1960\u201365\n|-\n|[[British Railways Mark 2|Mark 2]]\n|[[File:BR Mk.IIf TSO No.5976 (6801455419).jpg|120x120px|alt=]]\n|align=center|[[Passenger car (rail)|Coach]]\n|align=center|100\n|align=center|161\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|1963\u201375\n|-\n|}\n\n==Future fleet==\n\n[[File:British Rail Class 769.jpg|right|thumb|Former Class 319 Cheriton (unit 319008), destined to be a British Rail Class 769 at Cardiff Canton Depot. Awaiting final modifications before entering service with Transport for Wales Rail Services]]\n\nAll of TfW Rail's ATW-inherited and extra temporary fleet is due to be replaced by 2023 (with the exception of the Class 67 locomotives).<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00a3800m fleet renewal plan for new Welsh franchise |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/main-line/800m-fleet-renewal-plan-for-new-welsh-franchise/ |accessdate=2 April 2019 |work=International Railway Journal |publisher=Simmons-Boardman |date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Cascades and refurbishments===\n\n====Class 769 ''Flex'' units====\n\nNine [[British Rail Class 769|Class 769 ''Flex'']] bi-mode multiple units were due to be delivered by 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tfwrail/status/1080442677341110273|title=Hi Stuart, we're due to get 5 additional 153 units arriving from GWR by May, we're also getting class 769 flex trains this year and 3 sets of Mark 4 carriages from LNER. Then in the future, we're having new trains built ^Joy|last=Rail|first=Trafnidiaeth Cymru Trenau Transport for Wales|date=2 January 2019|website=@tfwrail|language=en|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref> following conversion from [[British Rail Class 319|Class 319]] electric multiple units which were previously in service with [[Govia Thameslink Railway|Thameslink]], by fitting diesel generators and extra electronic equipment to some previously unused below-solebar space.<ref>{{cite news |title=More '769s' on their way to Wales |work=RAIL Magazine |issue=872 |publisher=Bauer Media |date=13 February 2019}}</ref> This work has been delayed for a number of operators who wished to run the ''Flex'' units, including [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]] and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]]. The expected delivery date of May was not achieved, and in July 2019 TfW confirmed that regulatory issues with the units were preventing their introduction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/tfwrail/status/1147458016683397129|title=Hi Chris, we already have some class 769 units and they are currently in our depots undergoing maintenance for compliance issues ^Cam|last=Rail|first=Trafnidiaeth Cymru Trenau Transport for Wales|date=6 July 2019|website=@tfwrail|language=en|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref> As of 16 March 2020, only 4 769s have been delivered, though test runs on the Rhymney Line commenced on the same day. These units are currently expected to enter service sometime in 2020.\n\n====Class 67-hauled Mark 4 sets====\n\nIn addition, at least three Class 67 locomotives have been adapted to work with 12 (4 each) [[British Rail Mark 4|Mark 4]] carriages and 3 (1 each) Mark 4 [[Driving Van Trailer|DVTs]] from [[London North Eastern Railway]], which will replace the [[British Rail Mark 3|Mark 3]] stock currently used on locomotive-hauled services. These were able to cascade as a result of the introduction of [[British Rail Class 800|Class 800s]] on the [[East Coast Main Line]]. Testing and training of these sets commenced on 28 January 2020, and they are expected to enter service by mid-2020.\n\n====Class 230 ''D-Trains''====\n\nThe first \"new\" trains will also join the fleet during 2020 in the form of 5 {{brc|230}} ''D-Train'' diesel-battery-electric multiple units, which are being built in England from former [[London Underground D78 Stock]] aluminium bodyshells by start-up rolling stock manufacturer [[Vivarail]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New trains will be a boost for North Wales rail passengers |url=https://gov.wales/new-trains-will-be-boost-north-wales-rail-passengers?hootPostID=c053a7d5d26bdfd17f410c2930deda83 |accessdate=2 April 2019 |work=Press Release |publisher=Welsh Government |date=28 March 2019}}</ref> The first Class 230 units were delivered to [[West Midlands Trains|London Northwestern Railway]] in April 2019, on the [[Marston Vale Line]]. The five-month delay for introduction of these services indicated however that the units will also be delayed on the North Wales mainline (they were supposed to be introduced in 2019). On 9 September 2019, a test unit that was reconfigured to the same configuration as the TfW Rail units commenced test runs in the manufacturer's area, and on 10 April 2020, 230006 was the first TfW Rail unit to undergo testing there. The units are currently expected to enter service sometime in 2020.\n\n===New rolling stock orders===\nFor the longer term fleet replacement, 148 brand new trains have been ordered.\n\n====Class 197 ''Civitys''====\n\nA total of 77 Class 197 [[CAF Civity|CAF ''Civity'']] diesel multiple units have been ordered, which are due to be assembled in Wales at [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]'s new [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles#Newport factory, South Wales, UK|UK factory in Llanwern]], Newport.<ref>{{cite news |title=CAF commences design and engineering on DMUs for Wales and Borders franchise |url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/caf-commences-design-and-engineering-on-dmus-for-wales-and-borders-franchise |accessdate=2 April 2019 |work=Rail Technology Magazine |publisher=Cognitive Publishing |date=21 February 2019}}</ref> These trains will have end gangways. The first Class 197 Driving Motor carriage vehicle bodyshell was assembled, welded and painted in Spain by 12 February 2020; the bodyshells will be shipped to Newport for fitment of all components.\n\n====Class 756/231 ''FLIRTs'' and Class 398 ''Citylinks''====\n\nAlso, a total of 35 [[Stadler FLIRT|Stadler ''FLIRT'']] units have been ordered (consisting of 24 Class 756 tri-modes and 11 Class 231 diesel-electrics) along with 36 Class 398 [[Stadler Citylink|Stadler ''Citylink'']] tram-trains.<ref>{{cite news |title=STADLER TO DELIVER 71 NEW TRAINS FOR WALES & BORDERS |url=https://www.stadlerrail.com/en/media/article/stadler-to-deliver-71-new-trains-for-wales-and-borders/287/ |accessdate=2 April 2019 |work=Press Release |publisher=Stadler Rail AG |date=28 February 2019}}</ref> These will be manufactured at the Stadler factory in Szolnok, Hungary and assembled at their plant in Bussnang, Switzerland. The addition of these trains to the fleet, from 2021-24 but mostly in 2022\u201323, will allow the 109 (total) Class 150, 153 (13 by then), 158, 175 and 769 units to be withdrawn.\n\nAlongside the brand new fleet, the 170s will be retained for the duration of the franchise but will work different routes (including, but not limited to, West Wales services), with the 230s and Mark 4 sets also being retained and remaining on the routes they will work from their date of introduction on TfW Rail services.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Trainset\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Class\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Image\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! colspan=\"2\" |Top Speed\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Carriages\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Number\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Routes Operated\